{"title_page": "Denise Long Rife", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''Denise Long Rife''', born '''Denise Long''' (1951 \u2013 ) in [[Whitten, Iowa|Whitten]], Iowa''',''' a town of less than 200 inhabitants where her mother was the [[postmaster]],<ref name=\":0\" /> was the first woman drafted by a [[National Basketball Association]] team, although the Association's [[Commissioner of the NBA|Commissioner]] vetoed the pick because the NBA didn't draft players straight from high school at the time, nor women at any time.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Longman|first=Jer\u00e9|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/sports/basketball/first-woman-drafted-in-nba-avoids-coronavirus-but-not-its-frustrations.html|title=First Woman Drafted in N.B.A. Avoids Coronavirus, But Not Its Frustrations|date=April 1, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/2019/06/17/nba-draft-how-iowa-basketball-star-denise-long-rife-made-history-golden-state-warriors-girls-6-on-6/1409879001/|title=That time an Iowa girls' basketball star was drafted out of high school by the NBA's Warriors|website=Des Moines Register|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/2019/06/17/nba-draft-how-iowa-basketball-star-denise-long-rife-made-history-golden-state-warriors-girls-6-on-6/1409879001|title=That time the Warriors tried to draft girls' basketball star out of high school|last=Finney|first=Daniel P.|website=USA Today|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Golden State Warriors]] owner [[Franklin Mieuli]] picked her in the 13th round of the 1969 [[NBA draft]], but she played for a women's team\u2014the \"Warrior Girls Basketball League\"<ref name=\":0\" />--that the Warriors sponsored for one season<ref name=\":2\" /> rather than for the Warriors themselves.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/03/16/archives/the-road-to-glory-for-iowa-girls-basketball.html|title=The Road to Glory for Iowa Girls\u2014Basketball|last=Klemesrud|first=Judy|date=March 16, 1971|website=The New York Times|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> According to the Warriors' YouTube channel, she was picked to be the league's star.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EtZpAp3k8jI|title=Hear Us Roar: Denise Long|date=March 26, 2018|website=YouTube: Golden State Warriors channel|url-status=live|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> She was 19 years old, 5'11\" tall, and a graduate of Union-Whitten High School, where her class had only 34 students enrolled; the opportunity to go to San Francisco was irresistible.<ref name=\":2\" /> While there she met [[Wilt Chamberlain]], who joked that she had broken his triple-digit shooting record.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2018 the Warriors invited her and some of the other women from her league to a [[halftime ceremony]] honoring them during [[Women's History Month]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\nRife played [[Basketball positions|forward]] and was best at the long shot (before the 3-pointer became part of the game). At a time when \"combined final game scores often finished well above 200 points,\"<ref name=\":2\" /> she repeatedly scored over 100 points in a single high school game.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iowapbs.org/sports/story/5026/denise-long-rife-player|title=Denise (Long) Rife, Player|date=March 7, 2014|website=Iowa PBS|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> In one game, Rife recalled, a forward ended up guarding her because all the guards on the opposition's team had fouled out trying to keep her from scoring.<ref name=\":0\" /> Her career record of 6250 points lasted until [[Lynne Lorenzen]] bested her in the mid-1980s by nearly 500 points.<ref name=\":2\" /> She was inducted into the Iowa Girl's Basketball Hall of Fame in 1975.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/iahsaasports/hof-honors-and-awards/girls-basketball-hall-of-fame|title=Girl's Basketball Hall of Fame|website=Iowa High School Sports|url-status=live|archive-date=April 4, 2020|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn pre-[[Title IX]] America, \"[[Women's basketball|girls\u2019 basketball]] in Iowa did not need a federal mandate to be more popular than boys\u2019 basketball. ... The television audience for the girls\u2019 championship game drew as many as 3.5&nbsp;million viewers in nine Midwestern states,\"<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> and championship game week was the biggest week of the economic year for [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]] merchants.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1969/02/17/les-girls-in-des-moines|title=Les Girls in Des Moines|last=Mechem|first=Rose Mary|date=February 17, 1969|website=Vault|url-status=live|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> The 1968 championship game that her team won is available on [[YouTube]].<ref name=\":2\" /> As Rife noted, for girls in small-town Iowa, basketball could be a lifesaver.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHer prowess led to attention from ''[[Sports Illustrated]],''  which described her as \"all swiftness and grace\";<ref name=\":5\" /> ''[[The Tonight Show]],'' hosted at the time by fellow Iowan [[Johnny Carson]];<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> the [[The Wall Street Journal|''Wall Street Journal'',]]<ref name=\":0\" /> and other American media outlets. She was offered college scholarships but pre-Title IX women's college basketball was too limited to appeal to her.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn the era in question, women's high school basketball generally had 6-member teams and it was played as a half-court rather than full-court game, in which some of the offensive team players stayed back at their end of the court while the defensive team members followed their opponents to the other end of the court. During the summer of 1973, Rife played for the Venture Victory Team, \"a Christian team where we went over and gave testimonies and sang Christian songs at half-time\" during games against the Olympics teams from various Asian countries.<ref name=\":0\" /> This was full-court basketball, which she found challenging. In an interview with the Iowa [[PBS]] network, Rife discussed significant differences between the two versions of the game, explaining why women's basketball in her era was so exciting for audiences.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAfter basketball, she studied at various colleges where she got degrees in [[physical education]], in Bible theology, and eventually a degree in [[pharmacy]] from [[Drake University College of Pharmacy and Health Sciences|Drake University]].<ref name=\":2\" /> She worked as a pharmacist until retirement.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rife, Denise}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women's basketball players]]\n[[Category:People from Hardin County, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Iowa]]\n[[Category:Drake University alumni]]\n[[Category:American pharmacists]]\n[[Category:Women pharmacists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''Denise Long Rife''', born '''Denise Long''' (1951 \u2013 ) in [[Whitten, Iowa|Whitten]], Iowa''',''' a town of less than 200 inhabitants where her mother was the [[postmaster]],<ref name=\":0\" /> was the first woman drafted by a [[National Basketball Association]] team, although the Association's [[Commissioner of the NBA|Commissioner]] vetoed the pick because the NBA didn't draft players straight from high school at the time, nor women at any time.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Longman|first=Jer\u00e9|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/sports/basketball/first-woman-drafted-in-nba-avoids-coronavirus-but-not-its-frustrations.html|title=First Woman Drafted in N.B.A. Avoids Coronavirus, But Not Its Frustrations|date=April 1, 2020|work=The New York Times