{"title_page": "Beach Head War Cemetery", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Anzio War Cemetery|Sicily\u2013Rome American Cemetery and Memorial}}\n\n{{Infobox cemetery\n\n| name        = Beach Head War Cemetery\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| map_type    = \n| map_size    = \n| map_caption = \n| established = \n| country     = [[Italy]]\n| location    = [[Anzio]], [[Lazio]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|41.482|12.625|display=inline}}\n| type        = \n| style       =\n| owner       = [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]]\n| size        = \n| graves      = 2,316\n| interments  = \n| cremations  = \n| leases      = \n| website     = [https://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/70511/beach-head-war-cemetery,-anzio/ CWGC official website]\n| findagraveid= 2148385\n}}\n\nThe '''Beach Head War Cemetery''' near [[Anzio]] is a [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] cemetery of the [[Second World War]]<ref name=\"CWGC\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/70511/beach-head-war-cemetery,-anzio/|accessdate=21 April 2020|title=Beach Head War Cemetery at CWGC website}}</ref>. It contains graves resulting mostly from [[Operation Shingle]] and subsequent military actions in [[Italy]].\n\nCemetery contains 2,316 Commonwealth burials of the Second World War, 2025<ref name=\"CWGC list\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find/find-war-dead/results/?cemetery=BEACH%20HEAD%20WAR%20CEMETERY,%20ANZIO|accessdate=21 April 2020|title=List of buried at CWGC website}}</ref>  of them identified, including [[Victoria Cross]] recipient, Sgt. [[Maurice Rogers]]<ref name=\"Rogers\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/2373895/rogers,-maurice-albert-wyndham/|accessdate=21 April 2020|title=Maurice Albert Windham Rogers at CWGC website}}</ref>. There is also one<ref name=\"Ellis\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/2000342/ellis,-silbert-george/|accessdate=21 April 2020|title=Silbert George Ellis at CWGC website}}</ref> [[First World War]] burial which was brought from Chieti Communal Cemetery near [[Rome]].\n\nCemetery was designed by British architect [[Louis de Soissons]]<ref name=\"CWGC\"/>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Anzio War Cemetery]]\n* [[Sicily\u2013Rome American Cemetery and Memorial]]\n* [[List of cemeteries in Italy]]\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Architecture|Italy|World War II}}\n[[Category:Burials in Lazio]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth War Graves Commission cemeteries in Italy]]\n[[Category:World War II operations and battles of the Italian Campaign]]\n[[Category:World War II cemeteries in Italy]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cemetery-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Anzio War Cemetery|Sicily\u2013Rome American Cemetery and Memorial}}\n\n{{Infobox cemetery\n\n| name        = Beach Head War Cemetery\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| map_type    = \n| map_size    = \n| map_caption = \n| established = \n| country     = [[Italy]]\n| location    = [[Anzio]], [[Lazio]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|41.482|12.625|display=inline}}\n| type        = \n| style       =\n| owner       = [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]]\n| size        = \n| graves      = 2,316\n| interments  = \n| cremations  = \n| leases      = \n| website     = [https://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/70511/beach-head-war-cemetery,-anzio/ CWGC official website]\n| findagraveid= 2148385\n}}\n\nThe '''Beach Head War Cemetery''' near [[Anzio]] is a [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] cemetery of the [[Second World War]]<ref name=\"CWGC\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/70511/beach-head-war-cemetery,-anzio/|accessdate=21 April 2020|title=Beach Head War Cemetery at CWGC website}}</ref>. It contains graves resulting mostly from [[Operation Shingle]] and subsequent military actions in [[Italy]].\n\nCemetery contains 2,316 Commonwealth burials of the Second World War, 2025<ref name=\"CWGC list\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find/find-war-dead/results/?cemetery=BEACH%20HEAD%20WAR%20CEMETERY,%20ANZIO|accessdate=21 April 2020|title=List of buried at CWGC website}}</ref>  of them identified, including [[Victoria Cross]] recipient, Sgt. Maurice Rogers<ref name=\"Rogers\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/2373895/rogers,-maurice-albert-wyndham/|accessdate=21 April 2020|title=Maurice Albert Windham Rogers at CWGC website}}</ref>. There is also one<ref name=\"Ellis\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/2000342/ellis,-silbert-george/|accessdate=21 April 2020|title=Silbert George Ellis at CWGC website}}</ref> [[First World War]] burial which was brought from Chieti Communal Cemetery near [[Rome]].\n\nCemetery was designed by British architect [[Louis de Soissons]]<ref name=\"CWGC\"/>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Anzio War Cemetery]]\n* [[Sicily\u2013Rome American Cemetery and Memorial]]\n* [[List of cemeteries in Italy]]\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Architecture|Italy|World War II}}\n[[Category:Burials in Lazio]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth War Graves Commission cemeteries in Italy]]\n[[Category:World War II operations and battles of the Italian Campaign]]\n[[Category:World War II cemeteries in Italy]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cemetery-stub}}\n", "name_user": "A.Petrenko", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beach_Head_War_Cemetery"}
{"title_page": "Charlie Bit My Finger", "text_new": "{{short description|2007 Internet viral video}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Charlie Bit My Finger!\n| image = Charlie Bit My Finger screenshot.png\n| caption = Harry and Charlie as seen in the video.\n| starring = Harry Davies-Carr<br>Charlie Davies-Carr\n| released = {{start date|df=y|2007|5|22}}\n| runtime = 55.7 seconds\n| country = [[United Kingdom]]\n}}\n\"'''Charlie bit my finger - again !'''\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/lowered-expectations-web-redefines-quality-2010-2|title= Lowered Expectations: Web Redefines 'Quality'|last=Learmonth |first=Michael|date=22 February 2010|work=[[Advertising Age]]|accessdate=21 March 2010}}</ref> more simply known as '''Charlie Bit My Finger''' or '''Charlie Bit Me''', is a 2007 internet [[viral video]] famous for formerly being the most viewed [[YouTube]] video.<ref name=\"Times\">{{cite news|url=http://technology.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/tech_and_web/the_web/article6898146.ece|title= Harry and Charlie Davies-Carr: Web gets taste for biting baby|last=Chittenden |first=Maurice |date=1 November 2009|work=[[The Times]]| accessdate=20 November 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Stack\">{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/technology/meet-youtubes-224-million-girl-natalie-tran/story-e6frfro0-1225843291213|title=Meet YouTube's 224 million girl, Natalie Tran |last=Stack |first=Brittany|date=21 March 2010|work=\u00a8[[The Sunday Telegraph]]|accessdate=21 March 2010}}</ref> As of January 2020, the video has received over 870 million views.\n\nThe 56-second-long video,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10803956|title=Kiwi Youtube viewers go their own way (+videos)|last=Morton|first=Jamie|date=7 May 2012|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> which was uploaded on [[YouTube]] in May 2007,<ref name=\"Hutcheon\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/once-bitten-now-watched-by-millions-on-youtube-20091103-hjsc.html|title=Once bitten, now watched by millions on YouTube|last=Hutcheon|first=Stephen|date=28 October 2009|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate= 20 November 2009}}</ref> features Harry Davies-Carr (who was aged three) and Charlie Davies-Carr (aged one), two brothers from the [[United Kingdom]]. The two are seen sitting in a chair when Harry puts his finger into Charlie's mouth and gets bitten. \"Charlie bit me,\" he observes and puts his finger back into Charlie's mouth, which gets it bitten harder. Harry, who is hurt, says \"Ouch\" repeatedly and his brother begins to giggle. Afterwards, Harry smiles and repeats \"Charlie bit me. And that really hurt.\"<ref name=\"Times\"/>\n\nAs of January 2020, it's marked as content for kids and has no comments anymore, since that pile of filth is making everyone's life worse.\n==Background==\n{{Quote box\n|quote=Even had I thought of trying to get my boys to do this I probably couldn't have, neither were coerced into any of this and neither were hurt (for very long anyway).|source=Howard Davies-Carr, father of the boys<ref>{{cite book|last= Jarboe|first=Greg|title=YouTube and Video Marketing: An Hour a Day|publisher=John Wiley and Sons|year=2009|page=129|chapter=Week II: Watch the Best Viral Videos of 2007|isbn=978-0-470-45969-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WaBicMvGidsC&pg=PT159 }}</ref>\n|width=20em\n|align=right\n}}\n\nHoward Davies-Carr, the father of the boys, said the video was \"simply an attempt to capture the boys growing up\". While watching the finger-biting scene on his camera after recording it, it \"didn't particularly stand out\". It was not until he transferred the video onto his computer a few weeks later and played it again that he found it to be comedic.<ref name=\"Allan\">{{cite news|title=Famous for 15 minutes? Who needs that long? Bedroom singers, leisure-park stunt riders and biting babies have all been REAL LIVES YouTube celebrities. How do they feel about their accidental stardom? |last=Allan|first=Vicky|date=30 May 2009|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]}}</ref>\n\nThe Davies-Carr family lives in the United Kingdom. Howard uploaded the video onto YouTube so that it could be watched by the boys' grandfather, who was living in the United States.<ref name=\"Times\"/> He chose YouTube because the size of the video file was so big that it could not be sent by email. Originally the video was set to private and he mentions, \"I was just about to remove (the video) before it exploded. but once it had (exploded) I had lost control of the clip anyway so I left it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.businessinsider.com/where-are-they-now-charlie-bit-my-finger-family-earned-tens-of-thousands-from-video-2010-7#ixzz2nBIez8y |title=WHERE ARE THEY NOW? \"Charlie Bit My Finger\" Family Earned \"Tens Of Thousands\" From Video |publisher=Business Insider |date=13 July 2010 |accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref> Howard commented on the video: \"The clip only went up as I wanted to share it with the boys' grandfather. I was naive about the whole YouTube thing. It became viral and once that happened there was nothing I could do. People have sent lovely comments and messages and I now upload a new video of the boys every six weeks.\"<ref name=\"Times\"/>\n\n==Views==\n\"Charlie Bit My Finger\" had received 2.6 million views on YouTube by the start of February 2008<ref>{{cite news|title=YouTube serves up some gems|last=Kinkead|first=Lucinda Dillon |date=3 February 2008|work=[[The Deseret News]]|page=B01}}</ref> and 12 million views by March 2008.<ref name=\"Laidman\">{{cite news|url=http://ndsmcobserver.com/2008/03/an-eye-for-an-eye/ | title=An eye for an eye |last=Laidman|first=Andrea|date=18 March 2008|work=The Observer|publisher=[[University of Notre Dame]]|accessdate=20 November 2009}}</ref> In December 2008, it was the twelfth most viewed video on YouTube with 65 million views.<ref name=\"Moore\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/3564392/Finger-biting-brothers-become-YouTube-hit.html|title=Finger-biting brothers become YouTube hit |last=Moore |first=Matthew|date=5 December 2008|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=20 November 2009}}</ref> By April 2009, the video had received 92 million hits.<ref name=\"Sostek\">{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/nation/2009/04/20/In-4-years-YouTube-succeeded-in-catching-world-s-eye/stories/200904200110|title=In 4 years, YouTube succeeded in catching world's eye|last=Sostek|first=Anya|date=20 April 2009|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|accessdate=20 November 2009}}</ref> It became the second most viewed video in August 2009,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/news/6092625/YouTube-to-allow-creators-to-cash-in-on-their-15-minutes-of-viral-fame.html|title=YouTube to allow creators to cash in on their 15 minutes of viral fame|last=Neate |first=Rupert|date=26 August 2009|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=20 November 2009}}</ref> and took over the title as the most viewed video ever at the end of October 2009, when it surpassed ''[[Judson Laipply|Evolution of Dance]]''.<ref name=\"Times\"/> By November 2009, \"Charlie Bit My Finger&nbsp;\u2013 Again!\" had received over 130 million views.<ref name=\"Times\"/> In addition to being the most viewed, it was also the \"most favourited\" and the second \"most discussed\" video on the website in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"Hutcheon\"/> In a May 2009 report compiled by Visible Measures, which measures video hits across 150 video-sharing websites, \"Charlie Bit My Finger\" was the thirteenth most viewed viral video on the Internet.<ref name=\"Moses\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/technology/web/rapper-tops-viral-video-list-as-boyle-closes-in/2009/05/06/1241289213149.html|title=Rapper tops viral video list as Boyle closes in|last=Moses|first=Asher|date=6 May 2009|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=20 November 2009}}</ref> \n\nBy the end of 2011, it had been surpassed by music videos [[Justin Bieber]]'s \"[[Baby (Justin Bieber song)|Baby]]\", [[Lady Gaga]]'s \"[[Bad Romance]]\", [[Eminem]] feat. [[Rihanna]]'s \"[[Love the Way You Lie]]\", [[Shakira]]'s \"[[Waka Waka (This Time for Africa)]]\" and [[Jennifer Lopez]] feat. [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]]'s \"[[On The Floor]]\", becoming the 6th most viewed video on YouTube. Despite being able to regain its position to number 3 (and becoming the third YouTube video to reach 800 million views), it has been since surpassed by many other videos, dropping out of [[List of most-viewed YouTube videos|30 most viewed YouTube videos]]. As of September 2019 it has received over 870 million views.<ref name=\"tube\" />\n\nDue to YouTube's new [[Children's Online Privacy Protection Act|COPPA]] regulations that started in January 2020, the video has been set as made for kids, therefore, the comments have been disabled.<ref name=\"tube\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_OBlgSz8sSM|title=Charlie bit my finger - again !|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=21 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nAs a result of the video's inadvertent fame, the boys gained recognition. Following the video, multiple clips were uploaded by their father to YouTube. They feature Jasper, the third child in the family. Shelley Davies-Carr, their mother, commented on the success: \"[[Susan Boyle]] has never had the hits we have had. The video got on to a college networking site in the U.S. and from there it went viral. I think the [[British accent]]s have helped make it so globally viewed.\"<ref name=\"Times\"/> According to a 2008 interview with Shelley, the boys get embarrassed when they see themselves on television. She also noted that in 2008 they were \"shy about their new fame.\"<ref name=\"Moore\"/><ref name=\"Wheeler\">{{cite news|title=You've been famed - Exclusive|last=Wheeler|first=Virginia|date=5 December 2008|work=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]|page=49}}</ref> Howard commented in 2009 that his sons \"are now almost legendary. People want their autographs, it's just crazy.\"<ref name=\"Hutcheon\"/><ref name=\"Wheeler\"/>\n\nIn their list of YouTube's 50 greatest viral videos, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' ranked \"Charlie Bit My Finger\" as number one.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/0,28757,1974961,00.html|title= YouTube's 50 Best Videos |date=29 March 2010|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=11 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe video's lasting impact was underscored by the Davies-Carr family's appearance as mystery guests on [[Channel 4]]'s ''[[The Big Fat Quiz of the Year|Big Fat Quiz of the '00s]]'' on 30 September 2012. Among the references to the video includes an episode of the U.S. television series ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]''.\n\nIn a 2012 interview Howard Davies-Carr discussed the pitfalls of his sons' accidental fame saying, \"There are an awful lot of unscrupulous people out there who will try and take advantage of people that don't understand what they have.\"<ref name=\"ABC news\">{{cite news|last=Kofman|first=Jeffrey|title=How 'Charlie Bit Me,' the Most Watched YouTube Clip Ever, Changed a Family's Fortunes |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/charlie-bit-watched-youtube-clip-changed-familys-fortunes/story?id=16029675|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=[[ABC News]]|date=29 April 2012}}</ref> When it comes to the topic of the boys getting older, the boys' father has reflected, \"When the boys get to 18, I'd like them to think back and think, 'O.K., I've got something in my life which is more than just what I was when I did the 'Charlie Bit Me' video.\"\n\nThe parents have passed on invitations to talk shows and on making public appearances in media outlets.<ref name=\"ABC news\" />\n\nIn 2014, during his \"After The Oscar's Special\" on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'', [[Jimmy Kimmel]] enlisted the help of many big-name celebrities to showcase some of YouTube's greatest videos. The first video to be showcased was \"Charlie Bit My Finger\" and was parodied in a video entitled \"Bitman Begins\" and featured [[Tom Hanks]], [[Meryl Streep]], and brothers [[Chris Hemsworth|Chris]] & [[Liam Hemsworth|Liam]] Hemsworth. Chris played the role of Harry, while Liam played the role of Charlie. The video was a mock trailer for a film featuring the actors. The climactic scene takes place on the roof of a building where Harry wants revenge on Charlie for biting his finger. \"Harry\" screams the line \"Charlie bit me, Charlie bit my finger!\" They fall off the roof onto the street below. \"Harry\" then utters the famous line \"Ouch Charlie, that really hurt\" while \"Charlie\" just laughs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GHfg6apNWcA&index=4&list=PL266EB39E46C6A1C8|title=#Kimmel YouTube Film -- Bitman Begins|date=2 March 2014|publisher=Jimmy Kimmel Live|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn an April 2015 interview, Charlie said he thought it was \"a bit odd that loads of people have watched it.\" Also according to the interview, Charlie and Harry's parents have made \"thousands\" from the video through advertising and sponsorship.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/the-filter/virals/11560252/Charlie-bit-my-finger-what-the-boys-look-like-now.html | title=Charlie bit my finger: what the boys look like now | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=24 April 2015 | accessdate=27 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Davies-Carr family now includes two additional sons, Jasper and Rupert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/04/23/charlie-bit-my-finger-kids-grown-up_n_7126098.html|title=Here's What The 'Charlie Bit My Finger' Kids Look Like Now|first=Bill|last=Bradley|publisher=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=23 April 2015}}\n</ref>\n\n[[Osama bin Laden]] had the video in his computer's audio/visual collection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/selectall/2017/11/charlie-bit-my-finger-video-found-on-bin-ladens-computer.html|title=CIA Confirms \u2018Charlie Bit My Finger\u2019 Was on One of Osama bin Laden\u2019s Computers|first=Madison Malone|last=Kircher|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nA sound-clip from this video features in the first track (\"Pulse 8\") of the 2015 album [[Integrity_(album)|Integrity]] by grime MC [[Jme_(MC)|Jme]].<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LVdNt2Mmk10</ref>\n\n==Financial impact==\nIt was reported that in 2011 the family made over \u00a3100,000 in advertising revenue from the video. The profit from the video was enough that the family could afford to purchase a new house.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ransom|first=Diana|title=Earning Cash With YouTube Videos | url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052748704122904575314851538643196 | accessdate=21 June 2010|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=18 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nTheir success has been compared to winning a lottery, a so-called \"meme lottery\".<ref name=\"ABC news\" /> Since the \"Charlie Bit My Finger\" video was posted, other videos of babies have gone \"viral\" on YouTube and the families are monetising them, often making over US$100,000.<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Claire|title=Cashing In on Your Hit YouTube Video |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/27/technology/personaltech/cashing-in-on-your-hit-youtube-video.html?_r=0|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=26 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn response to requests from viewers online the family created \"Charlie Bit My Finger\" T-shirts, mugs and limited edition calendars.<ref name=\"Times\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firebrandstore.com/charlie-bit-me|title=Charlie Bit Me|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011041047/http://firebrandstore.com/charlie-bit-me|archivedate=11 October 2013|website=firebrandstore.com|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe family signed into a partnership with a Viral Spiral, a viral meme video management company specialising in viral videos, which has helped place the viral video in meme advertisements for companies like [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]] and helped to create a viral meme brand.<ref name=\"ABC news\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/uk_news/Tech/article991534.ece |title=Now Charlie can bite your finger too \u2013 for a profit |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=11 March 2012 |accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref> There was also news of a web series featuring the boys in the works.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://betabeat.com/2012/10/charlie-bit-me-kids-getting-their-own-web-show-even-though-its-no-longer-2007 |title=Charlie Bit Me\u2019 Kids Getting Their Own Web Show Even Though It\u2019s No Longer 2007 |publisher=Beta Beat |date=10 October 2012 |accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|England|Internet}}\n*[[David After Dentist]]\n*[[Laughing Baby]]\n*[[List of Internet phenomena]]\n*[[List of most viewed YouTube videos]]\n*[[Viral video]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|_OBlgSz8sSM}}\n* {{imdbtitle|2140782}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|ach}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Evolution of Dance]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title = [[List of most viewed YouTube videos|Most Viewed Video on YouTube]]|years=Ranked 70th as of January 2017}}\n{{s-aft|after = [[Bad Romance|Lady Gaga \u2014 Bad Romance]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:2007 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2007 short films]]\n[[Category:2000s comedy films]]\n[[Category:British children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:British short films]]\n[[Category:British video bloggers]]\n[[Category:May 2007 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:Viral videos]]\n[[Category:2000s YouTube videos]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2007 Internet viral video}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Charlie Bit My Finger!\n| image = Charlie Bit My Finger screenshot.png\n| caption = Harry and Charlie as seen in the video.\n| starring = Harry Davies-Carr<br>Charlie Davies-Carr\n| released = {{start date|df=y|2007|5|22}}\n| runtime = 55.7 seconds\n| country = [[United Kingdom]]\n}}\n\"'''Charlie bit my finger - again !'''\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/lowered-expectations-web-redefines-quality-2010-2|title= Lowered Expectations: Web Redefines 'Quality'|last=Learmonth |first=Michael|date=22 February 2010|work=[[Advertising Age]]|accessdate=21 March 2010}}</ref> more simply known as '''Charlie Bit My Finger''' or '''Charlie Bit Me''', is a 2007 internet [[viral video]] famous for formerly being the most viewed [[YouTube]] video.<ref name=\"Times\">{{cite news|url=http://technology.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/tech_and_web/the_web/article6898146.ece|title= Harry and Charlie Davies-Carr: Web gets taste for biting baby|last=Chittenden |first=Maurice |date=1 November 2009|work=[[The Times]]| accessdate=20 November 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Stack\">{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/technology/meet-youtubes-224-million-girl-natalie-tran/story-e6frfro0-1225843291213|title=Meet YouTube's 224 million girl, Natalie Tran |last=Stack |first=Brittany|date=21 March 2010|work=\u00a8[[The Sunday Telegraph]]|accessdate=21 March 2010}}</ref> As of January 2020, the video has received over 870 million views.\n\nThe 56-second-long video,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10803956|title=Kiwi Youtube viewers go their own way (+videos)|last=Morton|first=Jamie|date=7 May 2012|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> which was uploaded on [[YouTube]] in May 2007,<ref name=\"Hutcheon\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/once-bitten-now-watched-by-millions-on-youtube-20091103-hjsc.html|title=Once bitten, now watched by millions on YouTube|last=Hutcheon|first=Stephen|date=28 October 2009|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate= 20 November 2009}}</ref> features Harry Davies-Carr (who was aged three) and Charlie Davies-Carr (aged one), two brothers from the [[United Kingdom]]. The two are seen sitting in a chair when Harry puts his finger into Charlie's mouth and gets bitten. \"Charlie bit me,\" he observes and puts his finger back into Charlie's mouth, which gets it bitten harder. Harry, who is hurt, says \"Ouch\" repeatedly and his brother begins to giggle. Afterwards, Harry smiles and repeats \"Charlie bit me. And that really hurt.\"<ref name=\"Times\"/>\n\n==Background==\n{{Quote box\n|quote=Even had I thought of trying to get my boys to do this I probably couldn't have, neither were coerced into any of this and neither were hurt (for very long anyway).|source=Howard Davies-Carr, father of the boys<ref>{{cite book|last= Jarboe|first=Greg|title=YouTube and Video Marketing: An Hour a Day|publisher=John Wiley and Sons|year=2009|page=129|chapter=Week II: Watch the Best Viral Videos of 2007|isbn=978-0-470-45969-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WaBicMvGidsC&pg=PT159 }}</ref>\n|width=20em\n|align=right\n}}\n\nHoward Davies-Carr, the father of the boys, said the video was \"simply an attempt to capture the boys growing up\". While watching the finger-biting scene on his camera after recording it, it \"didn't particularly stand out\". It was not until he transferred the video onto his computer a few weeks later and played it again that he found it to be comedic.<ref name=\"Allan\">{{cite news|title=Famous for 15 minutes? Who needs that long? Bedroom singers, leisure-park stunt riders and biting babies have all been REAL LIVES YouTube celebrities. How do they feel about their accidental stardom? |last=Allan|first=Vicky|date=30 May 2009|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]}}</ref>\n\nThe Davies-Carr family lives in the United Kingdom. Howard uploaded the video onto YouTube so that it could be watched by the boys' grandfather, who was living in the United States.<ref name=\"Times\"/> He chose YouTube because the size of the video file was so big that it could not be sent by email. Originally the video was set to private and he mentions, \"I was just about to remove (the video) before it exploded. but once it had (exploded) I had lost control of the clip anyway so I left it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.businessinsider.com/where-are-they-now-charlie-bit-my-finger-family-earned-tens-of-thousands-from-video-2010-7#ixzz2nBIez8y |title=WHERE ARE THEY NOW? \"Charlie Bit My Finger\" Family Earned \"Tens Of Thousands\" From Video |publisher=Business Insider |date=13 July 2010 |accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref> Howard commented on the video: \"The clip only went up as I wanted to share it with the boys' grandfather. I was naive about the whole YouTube thing. It became viral and once that happened there was nothing I could do. People have sent lovely comments and messages and I now upload a new video of the boys every six weeks.\"<ref name=\"Times\"/>\n\n==Views==\n\"Charlie Bit My Finger\" had received 2.6 million views on YouTube by the start of February 2008<ref>{{cite news|title=YouTube serves up some gems|last=Kinkead|first=Lucinda Dillon |date=3 February 2008|work=[[The Deseret News]]|page=B01}}</ref> and 12 million views by March 2008.<ref name=\"Laidman\">{{cite news|url=http://ndsmcobserver.com/2008/03/an-eye-for-an-eye/ | title=An eye for an eye |last=Laidman|first=Andrea|date=18 March 2008|work=The Observer|publisher=[[University of Notre Dame]]|accessdate=20 November 2009}}</ref> In December 2008, it was the twelfth most viewed video on YouTube with 65 million views.<ref name=\"Moore\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/3564392/Finger-biting-brothers-become-YouTube-hit.html|title=Finger-biting brothers become YouTube hit |last=Moore |first=Matthew|date=5 December 2008|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=20 November 2009}}</ref> By April 2009, the video had received 92 million hits.<ref name=\"Sostek\">{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/nation/2009/04/20/In-4-years-YouTube-succeeded-in-catching-world-s-eye/stories/200904200110|title=In 4 years, YouTube succeeded in catching world's eye|last=Sostek|first=Anya|date=20 April 2009|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|accessdate=20 November 2009}}</ref> It became the second most viewed video in August 2009,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/news/6092625/YouTube-to-allow-creators-to-cash-in-on-their-15-minutes-of-viral-fame.html|title=YouTube to allow creators to cash in on their 15 minutes of viral fame|last=Neate |first=Rupert|date=26 August 2009|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=20 November 2009}}</ref> and took over the title as the most viewed video ever at the end of October 2009, when it surpassed ''[[Judson Laipply|Evolution of Dance]]''.<ref name=\"Times\"/> By November 2009, \"Charlie Bit My Finger&nbsp;\u2013 Again!\" had received over 130 million views.<ref name=\"Times\"/> In addition to being the most viewed, it was also the \"most favourited\" and the second \"most discussed\" video on the website in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"Hutcheon\"/> In a May 2009 report compiled by Visible Measures, which measures video hits across 150 video-sharing websites, \"Charlie Bit My Finger\" was the thirteenth most viewed viral video on the Internet.<ref name=\"Moses\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/technology/web/rapper-tops-viral-video-list-as-boyle-closes-in/2009/05/06/1241289213149.html|title=Rapper tops viral video list as Boyle closes in|last=Moses|first=Asher|date=6 May 2009|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=20 November 2009}}</ref> \n\nBy the end of 2011, it had been surpassed by music videos [[Justin Bieber]]'s \"[[Baby (Justin Bieber song)|Baby]]\", [[Lady Gaga]]'s \"[[Bad Romance]]\", [[Eminem]] feat. [[Rihanna]]'s \"[[Love the Way You Lie]]\", [[Shakira]]'s \"[[Waka Waka (This Time for Africa)]]\" and [[Jennifer Lopez]] feat. [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]]'s \"[[On The Floor]]\", becoming the 6th most viewed video on YouTube. Despite being able to regain its position to number 3 (and becoming the third YouTube video to reach 800 million views), it has been since surpassed by many other videos, dropping out of [[List of most-viewed YouTube videos|30 most viewed YouTube videos]]. As of September 2019 it has received over 870 million views.<ref name=\"tube\" />\n\nDue to YouTube's new [[Children's Online Privacy Protection Act|COPPA]] regulations that started in January 2020, the video has been set as made for kids, therefore, the comments have been disabled.<ref name=\"tube\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_OBlgSz8sSM|title=Charlie bit my finger - again !|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=21 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nAs a result of the video's inadvertent fame, the boys gained recognition. Following the video, multiple clips were uploaded by their father to YouTube. They feature Jasper, the third child in the family. Shelley Davies-Carr, their mother, commented on the success: \"[[Susan Boyle]] has never had the hits we have had. The video got on to a college networking site in the U.S. and from there it went viral. I think the [[British accent]]s have helped make it so globally viewed.\"<ref name=\"Times\"/> According to a 2008 interview with Shelley, the boys get embarrassed when they see themselves on television. She also noted that in 2008 they were \"shy about their new fame.\"<ref name=\"Moore\"/><ref name=\"Wheeler\">{{cite news|title=You've been famed - Exclusive|last=Wheeler|first=Virginia|date=5 December 2008|work=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]|page=49}}</ref> Howard commented in 2009 that his sons \"are now almost legendary. People want their autographs, it's just crazy.\"<ref name=\"Hutcheon\"/><ref name=\"Wheeler\"/>\n\nIn their list of YouTube's 50 greatest viral videos, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' ranked \"Charlie Bit My Finger\" as number one.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/0,28757,1974961,00.html|title= YouTube's 50 Best Videos |date=29 March 2010|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=11 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe video's lasting impact was underscored by the Davies-Carr family's appearance as mystery guests on [[Channel 4]]'s ''[[The Big Fat Quiz of the Year|Big Fat Quiz of the '00s]]'' on 30 September 2012. Among the references to the video includes an episode of the U.S. television series ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]''.\n\nIn a 2012 interview Howard Davies-Carr discussed the pitfalls of his sons' accidental fame saying, \"There are an awful lot of unscrupulous people out there who will try and take advantage of people that don't understand what they have.\"<ref name=\"ABC news\">{{cite news|last=Kofman|first=Jeffrey|title=How 'Charlie Bit Me,' the Most Watched YouTube Clip Ever, Changed a Family's Fortunes |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/charlie-bit-watched-youtube-clip-changed-familys-fortunes/story?id=16029675|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=[[ABC News]]|date=29 April 2012}}</ref> When it comes to the topic of the boys getting older, the boys' father has reflected, \"When the boys get to 18, I'd like them to think back and think, 'O.K., I've got something in my life which is more than just what I was when I did the 'Charlie Bit Me' video.\"\n\nThe parents have passed on invitations to talk shows and on making public appearances in media outlets.<ref name=\"ABC news\" />\n\nIn 2014, during his \"After The Oscar's Special\" on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'', [[Jimmy Kimmel]] enlisted the help of many big-name celebrities to showcase some of YouTube's greatest videos. The first video to be showcased was \"Charlie Bit My Finger\" and was parodied in a video entitled \"Bitman Begins\" and featured [[Tom Hanks]], [[Meryl Streep]], and brothers [[Chris Hemsworth|Chris]] & [[Liam Hemsworth|Liam]] Hemsworth. Chris played the role of Harry, while Liam played the role of Charlie. The video was a mock trailer for a film featuring the actors. The climactic scene takes place on the roof of a building where Harry wants revenge on Charlie for biting his finger. \"Harry\" screams the line \"Charlie bit me, Charlie bit my finger!\" They fall off the roof onto the street below. \"Harry\" then utters the famous line \"Ouch Charlie, that really hurt\" while \"Charlie\" just laughs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GHfg6apNWcA&index=4&list=PL266EB39E46C6A1C8|title=#Kimmel YouTube Film -- Bitman Begins|date=2 March 2014|publisher=Jimmy Kimmel Live|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn an April 2015 interview, Charlie said he thought it was \"a bit odd that loads of people have watched it.\" Also according to the interview, Charlie and Harry's parents have made \"thousands\" from the video through advertising and sponsorship.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/the-filter/virals/11560252/Charlie-bit-my-finger-what-the-boys-look-like-now.html | title=Charlie bit my finger: what the boys look like now | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=24 April 2015 | accessdate=27 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Davies-Carr family now includes two additional sons, Jasper and Rupert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/04/23/charlie-bit-my-finger-kids-grown-up_n_7126098.html|title=Here's What The 'Charlie Bit My Finger' Kids Look Like Now|first=Bill|last=Bradley|publisher=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=23 April 2015}}\n</ref>\n\n[[Osama bin Laden]] had the video in his computer's audio/visual collection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/selectall/2017/11/charlie-bit-my-finger-video-found-on-bin-ladens-computer.html|title=CIA Confirms \u2018Charlie Bit My Finger\u2019 Was on One of Osama bin Laden\u2019s Computers|first=Madison Malone|last=Kircher|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nA sound-clip from this video features in the first track (\"Pulse 8\") of the 2015 album [[Integrity_(album)|Integrity]] by grime MC [[Jme_(MC)|Jme]].<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LVdNt2Mmk10</ref>\n\n==Financial impact==\nIt was reported that in 2011 the family made over \u00a3100,000 in advertising revenue from the video. The profit from the video was enough that the family could afford to purchase a new house.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ransom|first=Diana|title=Earning Cash With YouTube Videos | url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052748704122904575314851538643196 | accessdate=21 June 2010|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=18 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nTheir success has been compared to winning a lottery, a so-called \"meme lottery\".<ref name=\"ABC news\" /> Since the \"Charlie Bit My Finger\" video was posted, other videos of babies have gone \"viral\" on YouTube and the families are monetising them, often making over US$100,000.<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Claire|title=Cashing In on Your Hit YouTube Video |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/27/technology/personaltech/cashing-in-on-your-hit-youtube-video.html?_r=0|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=26 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn response to requests from viewers online the family created \"Charlie Bit My Finger\" T-shirts, mugs and limited edition calendars.<ref name=\"Times\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firebrandstore.com/charlie-bit-me|title=Charlie Bit Me|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011041047/http://firebrandstore.com/charlie-bit-me|archivedate=11 October 2013|website=firebrandstore.com|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe family signed into a partnership with a Viral Spiral, a viral meme video management company specialising in viral videos, which has helped place the viral video in meme advertisements for companies like [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]] and helped to create a viral meme brand.<ref name=\"ABC news\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/uk_news/Tech/article991534.ece |title=Now Charlie can bite your finger too \u2013 for a profit |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=11 March 2012 |accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref> There was also news of a web series featuring the boys in the works.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://betabeat.com/2012/10/charlie-bit-me-kids-getting-their-own-web-show-even-though-its-no-longer-2007 |title=Charlie Bit Me\u2019 Kids Getting Their Own Web Show Even Though It\u2019s No Longer 2007 |publisher=Beta Beat |date=10 October 2012 |accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|England|Internet}}\n*[[David After Dentist]]\n*[[Laughing Baby]]\n*[[List of Internet phenomena]]\n*[[List of most viewed YouTube videos]]\n*[[Viral video]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|_OBlgSz8sSM}}\n* {{imdbtitle|2140782}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|ach}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Evolution of Dance]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title = [[List of most viewed YouTube videos|Most Viewed Video on YouTube]]|years=Ranked 70th as of January 2017}}\n{{s-aft|after = [[Bad Romance|Lady Gaga \u2014 Bad Romance]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:2007 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2007 short films]]\n[[Category:2000s comedy films]]\n[[Category:British children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:British short films]]\n[[Category:British video bloggers]]\n[[Category:May 2007 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:Viral videos]]\n[[Category:2000s YouTube videos]]\n", "name_user": "191.55.190.138", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlie_Bit_My_Finger"}
{"title_page": "Play (Moby album)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Play\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Moby]]\n| cover      = moby play.JPG\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1999|5|17}}\n| recorded   = August 1997\u20131999\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Moby's home studio, Manhattan, New York\n| genre      = [[Downtempo]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=63|s=12}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Mute Records|Mute]]|[[V2 Records|V2]]|[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]}}\n| producer   = Moby\n| prev_title = [[I Like to Score]]\n| prev_year  = 1997\n| next_title = [[MobySongs 1993\u20131998]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Play\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[Honey (Moby song)|Honey]]\n | single1date = {{Start date|1998|8|24}}\n | single2     = [[Run On (Moby song)|Run On]]\n | single2date = {{Start date|1999|4|26}}\n | single3     = [[Bodyrock (song)|Bodyrock]]\n | single3date = {{Start date|1999|7|12}}\n | single4     = [[Why Does My Heart Feel So Bad?]]\n | single4date = {{Start date|1999|10|11}}\n | single5     = [[Natural Blues]]\n | single5date = {{Start date|2000|3|6}}\n | single6     = [[Porcelain (song)|Porcelain]]\n | single6date = {{Start date|2000|6|12}}\n | single7     = [[South Side (song)|South Side]]\n | single7date = {{Start date|2000|11|7}}\n | single8     = [[Find My Baby]]\n | single8date = {{Start date|2000|11}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Play''''' is the fifth studio album by American [[electronica]] musician [[Moby]]. It was released on May 17, 1999 by [[Mute Records|Mute]] and [[V2 Records]]. Recording of the album began in mid-1997, following the release of his fourth album, ''[[Animal Rights (album)|Animal Rights]]'' (1996), which deviated from Moby's electronica style; his goal for ''Play'' was to return to this style of music. Originally intended to be his final record, the recording of the album took place at Moby's home studio in [[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]].\n\nWhile some of Moby's earlier work garnered critical and commercial success within the [[electronic dance music]] scene, ''Play'' was both a critical success and a commercial phenomenon. Initially issued to lackluster sales, it topped numerous album charts months after its release and was certified [[Music recording certification|platinum]] in more than 20 countries.<ref name=\"Roberts\"/> The album introduced Moby to a worldwide mainstream audience, not only through a large number of hit singles that helped the album to dominate worldwide charts for two years, but also through unprecedented licensing of his music in films, television, and commercial advertisements. ''Play'' eventually became the biggest-selling electronica album of all time, with over 12 million copies sold worldwide.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/moby-on-new-memoir-the-decade-in-nyc-that-changed-his-life-20160607 |title=Moby on New Memoir, the Decade in NYC That Changed His Life |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York |date=June 7, 2016 |accessdate=June 7, 2016 |last=Zlatopolsky |first=Ashley}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 and 2012, the album was ranked number 341 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's list of [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|the 500 greatest albums of all time]].<ref name=500greatest/><ref name=500greatest2/>\n\n==Background==\nThe second half of the 1990s saw Moby in career turmoil after years of being a successful [[techno]] [[Child prodigy|wunderkind]]. The release in 1996 of ''[[Animal Rights (album)|Animal Rights]]'', a dark, eclectic, guitar-fueled record built around the [[punk rock|punk]] and [[Heavy metal music|metal]] records that he loved as a teenager, proved a critical and commercial disaster that left him considering quitting music altogether and going back to school to study architecture. He explained: \"I was opening for [[Soundgarden]] and getting shit thrown at me every night onstage. I did my own tour and was playing to roughly fifty people a night.\" However, he claimed, \"I got one piece of fan mail from [[Terence Trent D'Arby]] and I got a phone call from [[Axl Rose]] saying he was listening to ''Animal Rights'' on repeat. [[Bono]] told me he loved ''Animal Rights''. So if you're gonna have three pieces of fan mail, that's the fan mail to get.\"<ref name=\"Christopher Weingarten\"/>\n\nMoby started work on the album in August 1997 and put it on hold several times to complete touring obligations.<ref name=CCD99>{{cite web |url=https://www.chaoscontrol.com/moby-1999/ |title=Moby |work=Chaos Control Digizine |year=1999 |accessdate=April 14, 2019 |last=Gourley |first=Bob}}</ref> Recording sessions took place in Moby's [[Mott Street]] home studio in Manhattan, New York. At the time, Moby planned on making the album his last before ending his career.<ref name=\"autobio\">{{cite book |title=[[Porcelain: A Memoir]] |publisher=[[Penguin Press]] |year=2016 |author=Moby |authorlink=Moby |isbn=978-1-59420-642-9}}</ref> ''Play'' was delayed due to Moby's dissatisfaction with the initial mix of the album that he had produced at home. A second mixing was completed in an outside studio before attempts in two other studios displayed similar results. After returning home and producing a mix by himself, Moby felt happy with it. In the end, Moby said that he had \"wasted a lot of time and money\".<ref name=CCD99/> Moby recalled a moment from March 1999, after ''Play'' had been mixed and sequenced, where he sat on the grass in [[Sara Delano Roosevelt Park]]: \"I was sitting by the little tire swings that had been chewed apart by the pit bulls [...] thinking to myself, 'When this record comes out, it will be the end of my career. I should start thinking about what else I can do.'\" At that point, he considered returning to school to become an architect.<ref name=RS2002>{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/mobys-home-made-heaven-57904/ |title=Moby's Home Made Heaven |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York |date=June 6, 2002 |accessdate=May 11, 2019 |last=Fricke |first=David |authorlink=David Fricke}}</ref>\n\nWhen he finished recording, there was no sign that the album would perform any differently than ''Animal Rights''. According to Moby, he shopped the record to every major label, from [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]] to [[Sony Music|Sony]] to [[RCA Records|RCA]], and was rejected every time. After [[V2 Records|V2]] finally picked it up, his publicist sent the record to journalists, many of whom declined to listen to it.<ref name=\"Christopher Weingarten\"/> According to Moby's manager Eric H\u00e4rle, their original goal was to sell 250,000 copies, which was what ''[[Everything Is Wrong (album)|Everything Is Wrong]]'', Moby's biggest-selling album at the time, had sold.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_EricHaerleInt.html |title=Interview with Eric H\u00e4rle, manager at DEF for Moby, Sonique, R\u00f6yksopp |work=[[HitQuarters]] |date=March 25, 2003 |accessdate=September 21, 2011 |last=Bouwman |first=Kimbel |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609212002/http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview%2Fopar%2Fintrview_EricHaerleInt.html |archivedate=June 9, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Composition and music ==\n''Play'' has been described as primarily a [[downtempo]] album.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://products.kitsapsun.com/archive/1999/08-05/0022_endfest__99.html |title=Endfest '99 |work=[[Kitsap Sun]] |last=McCarthy |first=Sean L. |date=August 5, 1999 |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Moby Puts V2 Debut in 'Play' |magazine=CMJ New Music Report |last=Ciabattoni |first=Steve |volume=58 |issue=619 |page=2 |issn=0890-0795 |publisher=CMJ Network, Inc. |date=May 24, 1999 }}</ref><ref name=complex>{{cite web |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2013/08/the-15-best-songs-from-the-electronica-era/moby-play-2 |title=The 15 Best Songs From the Electronica Era |work=[[Complex.com|Complex]] |author=808SJAKE |date=August 5, 2013 |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref> ''Complex'' wrote \"Moby's approach featured many live recordings and \"found sound\" (a colloquial term for [[field recording]]s), and the result was an organic downtempo masterpiece. Incorporating elements of [[rock and roll]], [[soul music|soul]], and [[hip hop music|hip-hop]] into his modern [[electronic music|electronic]] beats, Moby's Play perfectly distilled what was happening musically around the world.\"<ref name=complex/> According to ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' magazine's [[Will Hermes]], ''Play'' was \"the high-water mark for populist electronica\" and a \"millennial [[American folk music|roots]] and [[blues]] masterwork\",<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|location=New York|page=58|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UAUQ04BGfpUC&pg=PA58|title=Electronica|last=Hermes|first=Will|authorlink=Will Hermes|date=June 2004}}</ref> while John Bush from [[AllMusic]] said it balanced Moby's early electronica sound with \"the [[breakbeat]] techno evolution of the '90s\".<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/play-mw0000243891 |title=Play \u2013 Moby |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=September 21, 2011 |last=Bush |first=John}}</ref> ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' critic [[Jim DeRogatis]] noted its incorporation of such disparate musical influences as early blues, African-American folk music, [[gospel music|gospel]], [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[disco]] and techno, \"all within the context of his own distinctly melodic [[ambient music|ambient]] stylings.\"<ref name=\"CST\">{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4497147.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302025706/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4497147.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 2, 2017 |title=Moby, 'Play' (V2) |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=May 30, 1999 |accessdate=March 1, 2017 |last=DeRogatis |first=Jim |authorlink=Jim DeRogatis |url-access=subscription }}</ref> The album was particularly notable for its extensive use of samples from [[field recording]]s collected by [[Alan Lomax]] on the 1993 [[box set]] ''Sounds of the South: A Musical Journey from the Georgia Sea Islands to the Mississippi Delta''. Moby was introduced to the collection through a friend, Dimitri Ehrlich, who loaned the CDs to him.<ref name=\"Christopher Weingarten\"/> Most of the samples were short and constantly repeated throughout the songs. For example, \"Honey\" used a sample from [[Bessie Jones (American singer)|Bessie Jones]] that consisted of a conjunction of four verses that was repeated over twenty times. In the liner notes for the album, Moby gave \"special thanks to the Lomaxes and all of the archivists and music historians whose field recordings made this record possible.\"<ref name=\"notes\"/>\n\n== Release and promotion ==\nWhen ''Play'' was released on May 17, 1999, it underperformed commercially. In the United Kingdom, it debuted at number 33 on the [[UK Albums Chart]], but sales declined in the weeks immediately following its debut and the album spent only five further weeks inside the charts for the remainder of the year.<ref name=\"Haynes\">{{cite journal |url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/moby |title=Moby's 'Play' Becomes The Thriller Of Licensing |journal=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] |location=New York |date=March 12, 2013 |accessdate=June 11, 2017 |last=Haynes |first=Gavin}}</ref><ref name=\"UKchart\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/25243/moby/ |title=Moby |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017 |format=select \"Albums\" tab}}</ref> Moby stated, \"First show that I did on the tour for ''Play'' was in the basement of the [[Virgin Megastores|Virgin Megastore]] in [[Union Square, Manhattan|Union Square]]. Literally playing music while people were waiting in line buying CDs. Maybe forty people came.\"<ref name=\"Christopher Weingarten\"/> Despite the album's strong critical reviews, ''Play''{{'}}s songs received little airplay from radio stations or television networks such as [[MTV]].<ref name=\"Leland\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/11/magazine/advertisements-for-themselves.html |title=Advertisements for Themselves |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 11, 2001 |accessdate=June 11, 2017 |last=Leland |first=John}}</ref> While this lack of airplay further damaged the album's commercial prospects, Moby and his record label soon found another approach to increasing public exposure of the album, by way of licensing its songs to [[film]]s, [[television show]]s, and [[Television advertisement|commercials]].<ref name=\"Leland\"/> According to Moby, the goal behind the licensing of ''Play'' \"was simply to get people to hear the music,\" adding, \"Most of the licenses weren't particularly lucrative, but they enabled people to hear the music because otherwise the record wasn't being heard.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hotpress.com/Moby/music/interviews/Hot-Press-meets-Moby/10444002.html |title=Hot Press meets Moby |work=[[Hot Press]] |location=Dublin |date=November 18, 2013 |accessdate=June 11, 2017 |last=Sweeney |first=Eamon}}</ref> Eric H\u00e4rle later clarified that although many people believed the songs were pitched for advertisements as part of the marketing campaign for an album that did not fit with mainstream radio, the licensing actually came as a result of agencies asking for permission to use the music as soundbeds, attributing the music's popularity to its evocative and emotional nature.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/> Despite the heavy licensing, the advertisements selected were nevertheless carefully chosen and more requests were turned down than accepted.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/>\n\nThe licensing approach proved successful in increasing exposure to ''Play'', and subsequently radio and MTV airplay for the album's songs began to pick up.<ref name=\"Leland\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/friday_review/story/0,3605,217303,00.html |title=Plug and play |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |date=May 5, 2000 |accessdate=June 11, 2017 |last=Simpson |first=Dave}}</ref> On January 15, 2000, the album re-entered the UK charts, slowly climbing positions and finally reaching number one three months later on April 15, 2000, spending five weeks at the top.<ref name=\"UKchart\"/> On April 20, 2000, the producers of a British television program asked to use \"7\", the only track from ''Play'' that no one else had yet to license, for a television program. \"When the fax arrived\", said Moby's manager Barry Taylor, \"we celebrated.\"<ref name=\"Organization Moby\"/> Remaining on the chart for the remainder of the year and achieving an overall total of 81 weeks, ''Play'' became the fifth best-selling album of 2000 in the UK,<ref name=\"UKchart\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/assets/files/Yearly%20best%20sellers%20-%20albums.pdf |title=Yearly Best Selling Albums |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |accessdate=June 11, 2017}}</ref> as well as the year's best-selling [[independent record label|independent]] album.<ref name=\"Roberts\">{{cite book |last=Roberts |first=David |year=2006 |title=[[British Hit Singles & Albums]] |edition=19th |publisher=[[Guinness World Records|Guinness World Records Limited]] |location=London |isbn=1-904994-10-5 |page=372}}</ref> By October 2000, ''Play'' had attained platinum certifications in seventeen countries and topped the charts in seven.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2000/oct/15/life1.lifemagazine5 |title=Definitely Moby |work=[[The Observer]] |location=London |date=October 15, 2000 |accessdate=June 11, 2017 |last=Smith |first=Andrew}}</ref> Despite reaching only number 38 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], over two million copies were sold in the United States, with the album enjoying steady sales for months and constant popularity.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/?id=DxUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40 |title=Dance & Electronic Music |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume=113 |issue=29 |location=New York |date=July 21, 2001}}</ref> Moby would later recall:\n\n{{blockquote|Almost a year after it came out in 2000 I was opening up for [[Bush (band)|Bush]] on an [[MTV]] Campus Invasion Tour. It was degrading for the most part. Their audience had less than no interest in me. February in 2000, I was in [[Minnesota]], I was depressed and my manager called me to tell me that ''Play'' was number one in the UK, and had beat out [[Santana (band)|Santana]]'s ''[[Supernatural (Santana album)|Supernatural]]''. I was like, 'But the record came out 10 months ago.' That's when I knew, all of a sudden, that things were different. Then it was number one in France, in Australia, in Germany\u2014it just kept piling on. [...] The week ''Play'' was released, it sold, worldwide around 6,000 copies. Eleven months after ''Play'' was released, it was selling 150,000 copies a week. I was on tour constantly, drunk pretty much the entire time and it was just a blur. And then all of a sudden movie stars started coming to my concerts and I started getting invited to fancy parties and suddenly the journalists who wouldn't return my publicist's calls were talking about doing cover stories. It was a really odd phenomenon.<ref name=\"Christopher Weingarten\"/>}}\n\n''Play'' also found its major strengths on the support of its impressive string of eight hit singles, an unprecedented feat for an electronica album. Seven of those singles were UK top 40 hits\u2014\"Honey\", the first single, was already in the market in August 1998, nearly ten months before the release of the actual album. The final single choice was \"Find My Baby\", which appeared on some national charts three and a half years after. Twelve music videos were commissioned for a total of eight different singles, produced by a large number of directors, which included [[Jonas \u00c5kerlund]] (\"Porcelain\"), [[Roman Coppola]] (\"Honey\"), [[Joseph Kahn]] (\"South Side\"), and [[David LaChapelle]] (\"Natural Blues\"). The apparent result of the marketing strategy was that the album, after an unremarkable debut, stayed on the charts for several years and broke sales projections for Moby and for the dance music scene, which was not seen to be a dominant commercial genre in the US in the 1990s (as compared with in Europe, where Moby had initially found fame).{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n\nIn October 2000, a [[compilation album]] entitled ''[[Play: The B Sides]]'' was released, consisting of tracks released as [[A-side and B-side|B-sides]] on the album's singles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://moby.com/discography/play-the-b-sides/ |title=Play: The B Sides |publisher=Moby.com |accessdate=September 22, 2011 |author=Moby |authorlink=Moby}}</ref> A [[DVD]] titled ''Play: The DVD'', produced by Moby and [[Handsome Boy Records|Jeff Rogers]], was later released in July 2001 as a companion to ''Play'', featuring most of the accompanying music videos for the album's singles, an 88-minute [[megamix]] of all the remixes created for the album accompanied by visuals created in [[Toronto]] at Crush, led by director Kathi Prosser, a performance on ''[[Later... with Jools Holland]]'', a tour diary shot by Moby and edited by Tara Bethune-Leamen entitled ''Give an Idiot a Camcorder'', a DVD-ROM component where users are able to remix two of Moby's songs, and a bonus CD containing the aforementioned megamix.<ref>{{cite AV media notes |others=[[Moby]] |year=2001 |title=Play: The DVD |type=liner notes |publisher=[[Mute Records]] |id=7243 4 92573 9 9}}</ref> The package was later nominated for a [[Grammy Award for Best Music Film|Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video]].<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/?id=1Q8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA90&lpg=PA90 |title=Final Nominations For The 44th Annual Grammy Awards |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume=114 |issue=3 |location=New York |date=January 19, 2002|pages=90\u201391}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 84/100<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|4}}<ref name=\"CST\"/>\n| rev3 = ''[[Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s|Christgau's Consumer Guide]]''\n| rev3Score = A+<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xVQbszFuEGMC&pg=PA208 |chapter=Moby: Play |accessdate=October 3, 2015 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau |page=208 |title=[[Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s]] |publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]] |year=2000 |isbn=0-312-24560-2}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score = A\u2212<ref name=\"Browne\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.ew.com/article/1999/06/11/play |title=Play |journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |location=New York |date=June 11, 1999 |accessdate=September 15, 2012 |last=Browne |first=David |authorlink=David Browne (journalist)}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Grow out the roots |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |date=May 14, 1999 |last=Simpson |first=Dave}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = 8/10<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19990412173158reviews.html |title=Moby \u2013 Play |journal=[[NME]] |location=London |date=May 12, 1999 |accessdate=May 11, 2016 |last=Cigarettes |first=Johnny |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001006122253/http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19990412173158reviews.html |archivedate=October 6, 2000}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7score = 5/10<ref name=\"DiCrescenzo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/5344-play/ |title=Moby: Play |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=June 1, 1999 |accessdate=September 21, 2011 |last=DiCrescenzo |first=Brent}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev8score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Moby: Play |journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |location=London |issue=153 |date=June 1999 |page=109}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"RollingStone\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/play-19990624 |title=Play |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York |date=June 24, 1999 |accessdate=September 15, 2012 |last=Walters |first=Barry}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev10score = 9/10<ref name=\"Aaron\">{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/?id=I5x8l8IaNUMC&pg=PA125#v=onepage |title=The Agony and the Ecstasy |journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |volume=15 |issue=7 |location=New York |date=July 1999 |accessdate=July 2, 2013 |last=Aaron |first=Charles |authorlink=Charles Aaron |pages=125\u201326}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Play'' was met with widespread critical acclaim. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an average score of 84, based on 20 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/play/moby |title=Reviews for Play by Moby |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nReviewing for ''[[The Village Voice]]'' in 1999, [[Robert Christgau]] said the album's sampled recordings would not \"shout anywhere near as loud and clear\" without Moby's \"ministrations\u2014his grooves, his pacing, his textures, his harmonies, sometimes his tunes, and mostly his grooves, which honor not just dance music but the entire rock tradition it's part of.\"<ref name=\"VV\">{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=July 27, 1999|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv799-99.php|title=Consumer Guide|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|accessdate=July 2, 2013}}</ref> He deemed the album \"no more focused\" than Moby's previous \"brilliant messes\" but still \"one of those records whose drive to beauty should move anybody who just likes, well, music itself.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/play/1999-06.php|accessdate=July 2, 2013|title=Moby, Chemical Brothers, Salif Keita|journal=[[Playboy]]|location=Chicago|date=June 1999|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref> [[AllMusic]]'s John Bush felt ''Play'' showed Moby \"balancing his sublime early sound with the breakbeat techno evolution of the '90s\".<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/> Barry Walters from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' said \"the ebb and flow of eighteen concise, contrasting cuts writes a story about Moby's beautifully conflicted interior world while giving the outside planet beats and tunes on which to groove.\"<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/> [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]], writing in ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', said despite some needed editing, Moby's graceful soundscapes filter out the original recordings' antiquated sound and \"make the singers' heartache and hope seem fresh again.\"<ref name=\"Browne\"/> In a more critical appraisal, ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' reviewer Brent DiCrescenzo believed the \"raw magnetism\" of the sampled recordings was lost to \"innate digital recording techniques\", resulting in music that was \"fun and functional, yet disposable.\"<ref name=\"DiCrescenzo\"/>\n \nAt the end of 1999, ''Play'' was voted the year's best album in the [[Pazz & Jop]], an annual poll of American critics published in ''The Village Voice''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=February 22, 2000|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/pnj/pj99.php|title=Flak on Both Sides|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|accessdate=July 2, 2013}}</ref> Christgau, the poll's supervisor, ranked it second best on his own year-end list.<ref>{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=February 22, 2000|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/pnj/deans99.php|title=Pazz & Jop 1999: Dean's List|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|accessdate=October 3, 2015}}</ref> The following year, the album was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Music Performance]] at the [[42nd Annual Grammy Awards|42nd Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/2000/SHOWBIZ/Music/01/04/grammy.noms.01/list.html |title=42nd Annual Grammy Awards nominations |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=April 29, 2010 |date=January 4, 2000 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120722190443/http://transcripts.cnn.com/2000/SHOWBIZ/Music/01/04/grammy.noms.01/list.html |archivedate=July 22, 2012}}</ref> Since then, it has frequently been named one of the greatest albums of all-time; according to [[Acclaimed Music]], it is the 316th most ranked record on critics' all-time lists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/Moby.htm|title=Play|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=October 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119190211/http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/Moby.htm|archive-date=November 19, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[NPR]] named ''Play'' one of the 300 most important American records of the 20th century, as determined by the network's news and cultural programming staff, prominent critics, and scholars.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/programs/specials/vote/300.html|title=The NPR 300|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=October 3, 2015}}</ref> It was also ranked number 341 on ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s 2003 and 2012 lists of [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|the 500 greatest albums of all time]],<ref name=500greatest>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-19691231/play-moby-19691231|title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time \u2014 341: Play \u2013 Moby|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=New York|date=December 11, 2003|accessdate=March 5, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101220144740/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-19691231/play-moby-19691231|archivedate=December 20, 2010}}</ref><ref name=500greatest2>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/moby-play-20120524|title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time \u2014 341: Play \u2013 Moby|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=New York|date=May 31, 2012|accessdate=March 5, 2017}}</ref> and in 2005, a panel of recording industry pundits assembled by [[Channel 4]] voted ''Play'' the 63rd-best album ever.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/G/greatest/albums/index.html |year=2005 |title=The 100 Greatest Albums |publisher=[[Channel 4]] |accessdate=October 3, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051214163944/http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/G/greatest/albums/index.html |archivedate=December 14, 2005 |url-status=unfit }}</ref> The album was also included in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die|1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die: Revised and Updated Edition]]|editor1-last=Dimery|editor1-first=Robert|publisher=[[Universe Publishing|Universe]]|year=2010|isbn=978-0-7893-2074-2}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nAccording to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', \"''Play'' wasn't the first album to make a rock star out of an insular techno nerdnik, but it was the first to make one a pop sensation. [...] ''Play'' made [[postmodernism]] cuddly, slowly but surely striking a chord with critics and record-buyers alike.\"<ref name=\"Christopher Weingarten\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/play-10-years-later-mobys-track-by-track-guide-to-1999s-global-smash-20090702 |title=\"Play\" 10 Years Later: Moby's Track by Track Guide to 1999's Global Smash |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York |date=July 2, 2009 |accessdate=February 1, 2012 |last=Weingarten |first=Christopher R.}}</ref> According to ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' magazine, the songs on ''Play''\u2014which became the first album ever to have all of its tracks licensed for use in films, television shows or commercials\u2014\"have been sold hundreds of times&nbsp;... a licensing venture so staggeringly lucrative that the album was a financial success months before it reached its multi-platinum sales total.\"<ref name=\"Organization Moby\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/10.05/moby.html |title=Organization Moby |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |location=San Francisco |date=May 2002 |accessdate=September 21, 2011 |last=Smith |first=Ethan}}</ref> In a retrospective piece for ''[[EMusic|Wondering Sound]]'', [[Robert Christgau]] wrote:\n\n{{quote|Although some techno futurists still disparage the gorgeous ''Play'', it qualified as a futurist work simply by redefining the concept of \"commercial.\" Clubs would never take a CD mega, and no way could these anonymously sung tracks crack any hit-based radio format. So Moby's handlers swamped the mass market through the side door, placing swatches of all 18 songs (most many times) on movie and TV soundtracks and in ads for the likes of [[Volkswagen]], [[Baileys Irish Cream]] and [[American Express]]. [[FM broadcasting|FM]] exposure followed. But the main reason this album will sound familiar the way [[Symphony No. 9 (Beethoven)|Beethoven's Ninth]] does to a [[classical music|classical]] ignoramus is that little bits of it have seeped into most Americans' brains. For this be grateful, because those bits are intensely pleasurable as melody or texture or sometimes beat, and because Moby has ordered, paced, and segued them and their intimate surroundings into something that suggests a surging and receding whole. A [[Treacherous Three]] rap powers \"Bodyrock,\" but most of the identifiable sources are little-known blues and gospel singers first archived by folklorist [[Alan Lomax]]. Folk [[wikt:purist|purist]]s might well claim this re-use cheapens them. But here's betting musical folk like the singers themselves are plenty proud somewhere.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cdrev/moby-11.php |title=Moby, Play |work=[[Wondering Sound]] |date=April 11, 2011 |accessdate=October 3, 2015 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref>}}\n\nFurthermore, in an interview with ''Rolling Stone'', English singer-songwriter [[Adele]] credited ''Play'' as a major influence on her 2015 album ''[[25 (Adele album)|25]]'',<ref name=\"rs25\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/17-things-you-learn-hanging-out-with-adele-20151130 |title=17 Things You Learn Hanging Out With Adele |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York |date=November 30, 2015 |accessdate=November 30, 2015 |last=Hiatt |first=Brian}}</ref> stating:\n{{quote|There's something that I find really holy about that ''Play'' album... The way it makes me feel. Even though there's nothing holy or preachy about it. There's just something about it\u2014maybe the gospel samples. But it makes me feel alive, that album, still. And I remember my mum having that record.<ref name=\"rs25\"/>|sign=|source=}}\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = Moby, except where noted\n| total_length = 63:03\n| title1 = [[Honey (Moby song)|Honey]]\n| writer1 = Moby, [[Bessie Jones (American singer)|Bessie Jones]], [[Alan Lomax]]\n| length1 = 3:27\n| title2 = [[Find My Baby]]\n| writer2 = Moby, Willie Jones, Lomax\n| length2 = 3:58\n| title3 = [[Porcelain (song)|Porcelain]]\n| length3 = 4:01\n| title4 = [[Why Does My Heart Feel So Bad?]]\n| length4 = 4:23\n| title5 = [[South Side (song)|South Side]]\n| length5 = 3:48\n| title6 = Rushing\n| length6 = 2:58\n| title7 = [[Bodyrock (song)|Bodyrock]]\n| writer7 