aul|last=Sexton|date=18 November 2000}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Italy|type=album|artist=Moby|title=Play|award=Platinum|number=2|relyear=1999||certref=<ref name=\"billboard\"/>|accessdate=June 19, 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Netherlands|type=album|artist=Moby|accessdate=October 11, 2018|relyear=1999|certyear=2001|award=Platinum}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=New Zealand|artist=Moby|title=Play|certyear=1999|type=album|award= Platinum|number=7|id=1751|accessdate=February 3, 2015|certref=<ref name=nzcer>{{Cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=1117|title=Top 50 Singles Chart, 04 March 2001|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]]|accessdate=January 5, 2012}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Norway|type=album|artist=Moby|title=Play|relyear=2000|certyear=2001|award=Platinum|accessdate=February 9, 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Sweden|type=album|artist=Moby|title=Play|accessdate=July 25, 2012|relyear=1999|award=Platinum|certyear=1999}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Switzerland|type=album|artist=Moby|title=Play|accessdate=July 25, 2012|relyear=1999|award=Gold|number=3}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=album|artist=Moby|title=Play|award=Platinum|number=6|accessdate=July 25, 2012|relyear=1999|salesamount=1,819,938|salesref=<ref name=Canouk>{{cite news |url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/Q/Queen/2006/11/17/2391437.html |title=Queen rules \u2013 in album sales |work=[[Toronto Sun]] |date=November 17, 2006 |accessdate=October 23, 2011 |last=Harris |first=Bill}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=album|artist=Moby|title=Play|award=Platinum|number=2|accessdate=July 25, 2012|relyear=1999|salesamount=2,700,000|salesref=<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1046027/night-fever |title='Night' Fever |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |location=New York |date=March 30, 2008 |accessdate=March 5, 2013}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Summary}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Europe|type=album|artist=Moby|title=Play|accessdate=February 9, 2019|relyear=1999|award=Platinum|number=4|certyear=2001}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official}}\n* {{Discogs master|82202|Play|type=album}}\n* {{MusicBrainz release group|name=Play|id=7f6a4e72-9fee-39db-8817-63425f97a0f5}}\n\n{{Moby}}\n\n[[Category:1999 albums]]\n[[Category:Moby albums]]\n[[Category:Mute Records albums]]\n[[Category:V2 Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Moby]]\n", "name_user": "User-duck", "label": "safe", "comment": "Remove errant parameter.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Play_(Moby_album)"}
{"title_page": "William Howard Melish", "text_new": "{{short description|20th-century American Christian and civil rights leader}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = Episcopalian\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name             = Wiliam Howard Melish\n| honorific_suffix = \n| title            = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| church           = Holy Trinity Church, Brooklyn (renamed [[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]])\n| archdiocese      = \n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = \n| see              = \n| elected          = <!-- or | appointed = -->\n| term             = <!-- or term_start / term_end -->\n| quashed          = <!-- or | retired = -->\n| predecessor      =\n| successor        = \n| opposed          = \n| other_post       = \n---------- Personal details ----------\n| birth_name       = Wiliam Howard Melish\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1910|5|11}}\n| baptised         = <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| birth_place      = [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1986|6|15|1910|5|11}}\n| death_place      = [[Boerum Hill]], [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| buried           = <!-- or | tomb = -->\n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality      = American\n| religion         = [[Episcopalianism]]\n| residence        = \n| parents          = John Howard Melish, Marguerite McComas\n| spouse           = Mary Jane Dietz\n| children         = 3 sons\n| occupation       = Episcopalian assistant rector, civil rights activist\n| profession       = <!-- or | previous_post = -->\n| education        =  [[Harvard University]]; [[Jesus College, Cambridge]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Episcopal Theological School]]\n| motto            = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = \n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n}}\nReverend '''Wiliam Howard Melish''' (1910-1986) was an 20th-century American Episcopalian and social leader, driven from his Brooklyn church in the 1950s during [[McCarthyism]] in a decade-long controversy by the Episcopalian bishop of Long Island due to his association with the [[USSR]] and [[CPUSA]].<ref name=NYTobit>\n{{cite news\n| first = Wolfgang\n| last = Saxon\n| title = Rev. W. Howard Melish, 76, Dies; Ousted at Parish in McCarthy Era\n| newspaper = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1986/06/16/obituaries/rev-w-howard-melish-76-dies-ousted-at-parish-in-mccarthy-era.html\n| page = B12\n| date = 16 June 1986\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=CRDL>\n{{cite web\n| title = Melish, William Howard, 1910-\n| newspaper = Civil Rights Digital Library\n| url = http://crdl.usg.edu/people/m/melish_william_howard_1910/?Welcome\n| date = 2013\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=BHS>\n{{cite web\n| title = Guide to the John Howard Melish, William Howard Melish and Protestant Episcopal Church of the Holy Trinity collection ARC.050\n| publisher = Brooklyn Historical Society\n| url = http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/bhs/arc_050_melish/bioghist.html\n| date = 15 February 2012\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=SNAC>\n{{cite web\n| title = Church of the Holy Trinity (Brooklyn, New York, N.Y.)\n| publisher = Social Networks and Archival Context\n| url = http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/bhs/arc_050_melish/bioghist.html\n| date =\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nWilliam Howard Melish was born on May 11, 1910, in [[Brooklyn, New York]].  His parents were was Dr. [http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,794688,00.html John Howard Melish] and Marguerite McComas.<ref name=JADE>\n{{cite web\n| title = Melish, John Howard (1874-1969)\n| publisher = Jane Addams Digital Edition\n| url = https://digital.janeaddams.ramapo.edu/items/show/3723\n| date = 2010\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>  He studied at [[Harvard University]] and then studied for the priesthood at [[Jesus College, Cambridge]], and at the [[Episcopal Theological School]].<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=BHS/>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Ann n Holy Trinity CoE Montague St jeh.jpg|thumb|right|Melish led Holy Trinity Episcopal Church, depicted here as [[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]] in [[Brooklyn Heights, New York]].]]\nIn 1935, Melish began his ministry at Christ Church in Cincinnati, Ohio.  In 1938, he joined his father as assistant rector at the Holy Trinity Church in Brooklyn.  Melish served as assistant rector from 1938 to 1958; his father was rector there from 1904 until his ouster in 1949.<ref name=BHS/><ref name=SNAC/>\n\n===Political and civil activism===\n[[File:Joseph McCarthy adjusted.jpg|thumb|right|US Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] expressed concern with Melish over his chairmanship of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]].]]\nIn the 1940s, Melish joined the [[American Labor Party]] (then, affiliated with the [[Communist Party USA]]).  Melish was also a founding member of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]]<ref name=CRDL/>  Melish was also editor for the council's biweekly publication, ''Reporter (CPUSA)'' (an [[English-language press of the Communist Party USA]] publication).\n\nIn the same period, Melish supported the civil rights movement in the South; he served as a regional representative for ''Southern Patriot''  monthly periodical of the Southern Conference Educational Fund (successor to the [[Southern Conference for Human Welfare]]).<ref name=CRDL/>\n\n===Ouster===\n[[File:James_P._deWolfe.jpg|thumb|right|Bishop [[James P. DeWolfe]] of Long Island opposed Melish's chairmanship of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]].]]\nMr. Melish's chairmanship (1947\u20131951) of the National Council of American-Soviet Friendship led both him and his father into a \"bitter struggle\" in the 1940s and 1950s that divided their parish as the council wound up on the [[Attorney General's List of Subversive Organizations]] (AGLOSO) in December 1947.  Melish immediately and publicly opposed the AGLOSO, telling the ''New York Times'' that the :     <blockquote> <small> the National Council... \"was prepared to fight through the courts any such imputation of our loyalty... We are American citizens who stand for good relations between the United States and the Soviet Union as the key to peace...  It has always been the right of American citizens under the Constitution to discuss and, if need be, criticize the foreign policy of the United States.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Accused Groups Deny Disloyalty; Five Organizations Listed by U.S. Insist They Are Not Subversive, Assail Clark\n| newspaper = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1947/12/05/archives/accused-groups-deny-disloyalty-five-organizations-listed-by-us.html\n| page = 18\n| date = 5 December 1947\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref> </small> </blockquote>   US Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] investigated Melish as chairman of the council.  In 1957, Bishop [[James P. DeWolfe]] of the Episcopal Diocese of Long Island closed the Holy Trinity Church in Brooklyn in 1957 and ousted Melish, who had taken over from his father in 1949.  The bishop closed the church until a new congregation claimed it as \"[[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]].\"<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=BHS/>\n\n===''Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish''===\n\nThe rector, church wardens, and vestrymen of the Church of the Holy Trinity in Brooklyn sued Melish and his father to leave; they refused.  On June 24, 1957, the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of New York, Second Department, found in favor of the church.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish\n| publisher = CaseText\n| url = https://casetext.com/case/rector-church-of-holy-trinity-v-melish-1\n| date = 24 June 1957\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>    On March 26, 1958, the Supreme Court of [[Kings County, New York]], heard ''Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish''.  Hubbell and Davies represented the plaintiffs; Raphael H. Weissman and Hubert T. Delaney represented Melish.  The supreme court found in favor of the plaintiffs.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish\n| publisher = Leagle\n| url = https://www.leagle.com/decision/195833312misc2d3211224\n| date = 1958\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>  The case received press coverage, including ''Life'' magazine.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = 'Mr. Melish, You Are Out of Order'\n| magazine = Life\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=gT8EAAAAMBAJ\n| pages = 57-58\n| date = 30 January 1956\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Later life===\n\nAfter his ouster, Melish and his wife both visited the Soviet Union six times.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nIn 1963, Melish delivered an address at the memorial for [[W.E.B. DuBois]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Address delivered by the Rev. William Howard Melish at the memorial service of the late Dr. W. E. B. Du Bois at the Affrey Memorial Church, Achimota College, Accra, Ghana, ca. September 23, 1963\n| publisher = University of Massachusetts Amherst\n| url = https://credo.library.umass.edu/view/full/mums312-b287-i012\n| date = 23 September 1963\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1969, Melish became rector of [[Grace Episcopal Church Complex (Queens)]] for a decade until he retired in 1979.  He then returned to his Brooklyn church as an assisting priest until he died.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nIn 1971, Melish again became chairman of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]] until 1978.\n\n==Personal life and death==\n\nMelish married Mary Jane Dietz; they had three sons.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nMelish advocated civil rights.  He also advocated peaceful co-existence with the [[USSR]], which in July 1948 formed part of the foreign plank of the platform of the [[1948 Progressive Party of the United States].<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nMelish lived in the [[Boerum Hill]] section of Brooklyn, New York.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nMelish died age 76 on June 15, 1986, in Brooklyn.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Awards==\n\n* 1956:  [[World Peace Prize|International Peace Prize]] of the [[World Peace Council]]|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/04/28/archives/melish-is-honored-reddominated-world-peace-council-awards-prize.html|title=Melish is Honored; Red-Dominated World Peace Council Awards Prize|date=28 April 1956|page=6|accessdate=19 July 2010|work=New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]] \n* [[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.digitalcommonwealth.org/search?f%5Bname_facet_ssim%5D%5B%5D=Melish%2C+William+Howard%2C+1910- Digital Commonweath]\n* [http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/bhs/arc_050_melish/bioghist.html Brooklyn Historical Society]: Guide to the John Howard Melish, William Howard Melish and Protestant Episcopal Church of the Holy Trinity collection ARC.050\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/bud1929/6823486340 William Howard Melish (undated)]\n\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Episcopalian ministers]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York]]\n[[Category:American Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:American ethicists]]\n[[Category:American Episcopalian clergy]]\n[[Category:Christian clergy from New York]]\n[[Category:Christian ethicists]]\n[[Category:Christians from New York]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Episcopalian socialists]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from New York]]\n[[Category:Episcopal Theological School alumni]]\n\n {{US-Christian-clergy-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|20th-century American Christian and civil rights leader}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = Episcopalian\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name             = Wiliam Howard Melish\n| honorific_suffix = \n| title            = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| church           = Holy Trinity Church, Brooklyn (renamed [[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]])\n| archdiocese      = \n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = \n| see              = \n| elected          = <!-- or | appointed = -->\n| term             = <!-- or term_start / term_end -->\n| quashed          = <!-- or | retired = -->\n| predecessor      =\n| successor        = \n| opposed          = \n| other_post       = \n---------- Personal details ----------\n| birth_name       = Wiliam Howard Melish\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1910|5|11}}\n| baptised         = <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| birth_place      = [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1986|6|15|1910|5|11}}\n| death_place      = [[Boerum Hill]], [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| buried           = <!-- or | tomb = -->\n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality      = American\n| religion         = [[Episcopalianism]]\n| residence        = \n| parents          = John Howard Melish\n| spouse           = Mary Jane Dietz\n| children         = 3 sons\n| occupation       = Episcopalian assistant rector, civil rights activist\n| profession       = <!-- or | previous_post = -->\n| education        =  [[Harvard University]], [[Cambridge University]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Episcopal Theological School]]\n| motto            = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = \n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n}}\nReverend '''Wiliam Howard Melish''' (1874-1969) was an 20th-century American Episcopalian and social leader, driven from his Brooklyn church in the 1950s during [[McCarthyism]] in a decade-long controversy by the Episcopalian bishop of Long Island due to his association with the [[USSR]] and [[CPUSA]].<ref name=NYTobit>\n{{cite news\n| first = Wolfgang\n| last = Saxon\n| title = Rev. W. Howard Melish, 76, Dies; Ousted at Parish in McCarthy Era\n| newspaper = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1986/06/16/obituaries/rev-w-howard-melish-76-dies-ousted-at-parish-in-mccarthy-era.html\n| page = B12\n| date = 16 June 1986\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=CRDL>\n{{cite web\n| title = Melish, William Howard, 1910-\n| newspaper = Civil Rights Digital Library\n| url = http://crdl.usg.edu/people/m/melish_william_howard_1910/?Welcome\n| date = 2013\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=BHS>\n{{cite web\n| title = Guide to the John Howard Melish, William Howard Melish and Protestant Episcopal Church of the Holy Trinity collection ARC.050\n| publisher = Brooklyn Historical Society\n| url = http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/bhs/arc_050_melish/bioghist.html\n| date = 15 February 2012\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=SNAC>\n{{cite web\n| title = Church of the Holy Trinity (Brooklyn, New York, N.Y.)\n| publisher = Social Networks and Archival Context\n| url = http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/bhs/arc_050_melish/bioghist.html\n| date =\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nWilliam Howard Melish was born on May 11, 1910, in [[Brooklyn, New York]].  His parents were was Dr. [http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,794688,00.html John Howard Melish] and Marguerite McComas.<ref name=JADE>\n{{cite web\n| title = Melish, John Howard (1874-1969)\n| publisher = Jane Addams Digital Edition\n| url = https://digital.janeaddams.ramapo.edu/items/show/3723\n| date = 2010\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>  He studied at [[Harvard University]] and then studied for the priesthood at [[Jesus College]], [[Cambridge University]], and at the [[Episcopal Theological School]].<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=BHS/>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Ann n Holy Trinity CoE Montague St jeh.jpg|thumb|right|Melish led Holy Trinity Episcopal Church, depicted here as [[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]] in [[Brooklyn Heights, New York]].]]\nIn 1935, Melish began his ministry at Christ Church in Cincinnati, Ohio.  In 1938, he joined his father as assistant rector at the Holy Trinity Church in Brooklyn.  Melish served as assistant rector from 1938 to 1958; his father was rector there from 1904 until his ouster in 1949.<ref name=BHS/><ref name=SNAC/>\n\n===Political and civil activism===\n[[File:Joseph McCarthy adjusted.jpg|thumb|right|US Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] expressed concern with Melish over his chairmanship of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]].]]\nIn the 1940s, Melish joined the [[American Labor Party]] (then, affiliated with the [[Communist Party USA]]).  Melish was also a founding member of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]]<ref name=CRDL/>  Melish was also editor for the council's biweekly publication, ''Reporter (CPUSA)'' (an [[English-language press of the Communist Party USA]] publication).\n\nIn the same period, Melish supported the civil rights movement in the South; he served as a regional representative for ''Southern Patriot''  monthly periodical of the Southern Conference Educational Fund (successor to the [[Southern Conference for Human Welfare]]).<ref name=CRDL/>\n\n===Ouster===\n[[File:James_P._deWolfe.jpg|thumb|right|Bishop [[James P. DeWolfe]] of Long Island opposed Melish's chairmanship of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]].]]\nMr. Melish's chairmanship (1947\u20131951) of the National Council of American-Soviet Friendship led both him and his father into a \"bitter struggle\" in the 1940s and 1950s that divided their parish as the council wound up on the [[Attorney General's List of Subversive Organizations]] (AGLOSO) in December 1947.  Melish immediately and publicly opposed the AGLOSO, telling the ''New York Times'' that the :     <blockquote> <small> the National Council... \"was prepared to fight through the courts any such imputation of our loyalty... We are American citizens who stand for good relations between the United States and the Soviet Union as the key to peace...  It has always been the right of American citizens under the Constitution to discuss and, if need be, criticize the foreign policy of the United States.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Accused Groups Deny Disloyalty; Five Organizations Listed by U.S. Insist They Are Not Subversive, Assail Clark\n| newspaper = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1947/12/05/archives/accused-groups-deny-disloyalty-five-organizations-listed-by-us.html\n| page = 18\n| date = 5 December 1947\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref> </small> </blockquote>   US Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] investigated Melish as chairman of the council.  In 1957, Bishop [[James P. DeWolfe]] of the Episcopal Diocese of Long Island closed the Holy Trinity Church in Brooklyn in 1957 and ousted Melish, who had taken over from his father in 1949.  The bishop closed the church until a new congregation claimed it as \"[[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]].\"<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=BHS/>\n\n===''Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish''===\n\nThe rector, church wardens, and vestrymen of the Church of the Holy Trinity in Brooklyn sued Melish and his father to leave; they refused.  On June 24, 1957, the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of New York, Second Department, found in favor of the church.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish\n| publisher = CaseText\n| url = https://casetext.com/case/rector-church-of-holy-trinity-v-melish-1\n| date = 24 June 1957\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>    On March 26, 1958, the Supreme Court of [[Kings County, New York]], heard ''Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish''.  Hubbell and Davies represented the plaintiffs; Raphael H. Weissman and Hubert T. Delaney represented Melish.  The supreme court found in favor of the plaintiffs.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish\n| publisher = Leagle\n| url = https://www.leagle.com/decision/195833312misc2d3211224\n| date = 1958\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>  The case received press coverage, including ''Life'' magazine.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = 'Mr. Melish, You Are Out of Order'\n| magazine = Life\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=gT8EAAAAMBAJ\n| pages = 57-58\n| date = 30 January 1956\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Later life===\n\nAfter his ouster, Melish and his wife both visited the Soviet Union six times.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nIn 1963, Melish delivered an address at the memorial for [[W.E.B. DuBois]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Address delivered by the Rev. William Howard Melish at the memorial service of the late Dr. W. E. B. Du Bois at the Affrey Memorial Church, Achimota College, Accra, Ghana, ca. September 23, 1963\n| publisher = University of Massachusetts Amherst\n| url = https://credo.library.umass.edu/view/full/mums312-b287-i012\n| date = 23 September 1963\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1969, Melish became rector of [[Grace Episcopal Church Complex (Queens)]] for a decade until he retired in 1979.  He then returned to his Brooklyn church as an assisting priest until he died.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nIn 1971, Melish again became chairman of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]] until 1978.\n\n==Personal life and death==\n\nMelish married Mary Jane Dietz; they had three sons.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nMelish advocated civil rights.  He also advocated peaceful co-existence with the [[USSR]], which in July 1948 formed part of the foreign plank of the platform of the [[1948 Progressive Party of the United States].<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nMelish lived in the [[Boerum Hill]] section of Brooklyn, New York.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nMelish died age 76 on June 15, 1986, in Brooklyn.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Awards==\n\n* 1956:  [[World Peace Prize|International Peace Prize]] of the [[World Peace Council]]|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/04/28/archives/melish-is-honored-reddominated-world-peace-council-awards-prize.html|title=Melish is Honored; Red-Dominated World Peace Council Awards Prize|date=28 April 1956|page=6|accessdate=19 July 2010|work=New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]] \n* [[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.digitalcommonwealth.org/search?f%5Bname_facet_ssim%5D%5B%5D=Melish%2C+William+Howard%2C+1910- Digital Commonweath]\n* [http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/bhs/arc_050_melish/bioghist.html Brooklyn Historical Society]: Guide to the John Howard Melish, William Howard Melish and Protestant Episcopal Church of the Holy Trinity collection ARC.050\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/bud1929/6823486340 William Howard Melish (undated)]\n\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Episcopalian ministers]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York]]\n[[Category:American Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:American ethicists]]\n[[Category:American Episcopalian clergy]]\n[[Category:Christian clergy from New York]]\n[[Category:Christian ethicists]]\n[[Category:Christians from New York]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Episcopalian socialists]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from New York]]\n[[Category:Episcopal Theological School alumni]]\n\n {{US-Christian-clergy-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Aboudaqn", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor corrections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Howard_Melish"}
{"title_page": "Worshipful Company of Clockmakers", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox Livery Company\n| name        = Worshipful Company of Clockmakers\n| image       = Clockmakers Company Coat of Arms.jpg\n| caption     = Arms of the Clockmakers' Company, granted in January 1672. Blazon: ''Sable, a Clock ye Four Pillars thereof Erected on Four Lyons, and on Each Capital a Globe with a Cross, and in the Middest an Imperiall Crowne all Or, and for their Crest upon an Helmet Proper Mantled Gules Doubled Argent and Wreath of their Colours a Spheare Or, the Armes Supported by the Figures of a Naked Old Man Holding a Scithe and an Hour Glasse Representing Time, and of an Emperour in Roabes Crowned Holding a Scepter.''\n| motto       = ''Tempus Rerum Imperator''\n| location    = 1 Throgmorton Avenue, London EC2N 2BY\n| formation   = {{start date|df=yes|1631}}\n| association = Horology\n| precedence  = 61st\n| master      = Joanna Migdal (Lady White)\n| website     = {{url|clockmakers.org}}\n}}\n{{short description|Livery company of the City of London}}\nThe '''Worshipful Company of Clockmakers''' was established under a [[Royal Charter]] granted by [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] in 1631.<ref>https://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/royal-charters/list-of-charters-granted/</ref> It ranks sixty-first among the [[livery companies]] of the City of London, and comes under the jurisdiction of the [[Privy Council]]. The company established a library and its [[Clockmakers' Museum|Museum]] in 1813, which is the oldest specific collection of clocks and watches worldwide.<ref>https://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/see-and-do/clockmakers-museum</ref> This is administered by the company's affiliated charity, the Clockmakers\u2019 Charity,<ref>Charity No. 275380 registered with the UK Charity Commission</ref> and is presently housed on the second floor of London's [[Science Museum, London|Science Museum]]. The modern aims of the company and its Museum are charitable and educational, in particular to promote and preserve clockmaking and watchmaking, which as of 2019 were added to the [[HCA Red List of Endangered Crafts]].\n\n==Museum==\nThe [[Clockmakers' Museum|Clockmakers\u2019 Museum]], first established in 1813, was housed at London's [[Guildhall, London|Guildhall]] from 1874 to 2014. The collection of clocks and watches was moved to a new gallery provided by the Science Museum, officially opened by HRH [[Princess Anne]] on 22 October 2015. The company's archive and library are however still kept at [[Guildhall Library]]. The collection includes [[John Harrison|John Harrison's]] sea watch H5, once personally tested by [[King George III]].\n\n==Motto==\nThe company's motto, ''Tempus Rerum Imperator'', can be translated as \u2018Time, the Ruler of All Things\u2019. It appears as an epitaph on the tombstone of former British Prime Minister [[Harold Wilson]], a liveryman of the company. It has also been adopted by the [[Google Web Accelerator]] project.\n\n==History==\nPrior to the seventeenth century, clockmaking by native English craftsmen was mostly confined to the production of [[turret clocks]]. Domestic clocks and watches were mostly imported or the work of immigrants from the Continent. Because turret clock making involved working in ferrous metal, clockmakers within the City of London tended to be freemen of the [[Worshipful Company of Blacksmiths|Blacksmiths\u2019 Company]], though some were members of other livery companies, notably the [[Worshipful Company of Clothworkers|Clothworkers]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=English Lantern Clocks|last=White|first=George|publisher=ACC|year=1989|location=|pages=51\u201354}}</ref>\n\nAfter the loss of many London clock and watchmakers in the plagues of 1598 and 1603, the trade consolidated and began to grow. The continued influx of newcomers led to resentment from those who had become established in London towards outsiders who came to set up in or near the City and who threatened their market. From 1620 onwards, groups of clockmakers attempted to set up their own guild. The Blacksmiths initially succeeded in opposing these moves. Eventually, however, with the King issuing charters as a means of raising much needed finance at a time when he had prorogued Parliament, the clockmakers succeeded in securing a Royal Charter, on 22 August 1631, to the distress of the Blacksmiths, who could naturally expect to lose members, and therefore income.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Clockmakers of London|last=White|first=George|publisher=WCC|year=2018|location=London|pages=14\u201319}}</ref>\n\nThe Charter gave regulatory authority to the Clockmakers to control the horological trade in the City of London and for a radius of ten miles around. It incorporated a controlling body which should have \u2018continuance for ever under the style and name of The Master, Wardens and Fellowship of the Art and Mystery of Clockmaking\u2019. It provided that the Fellowship should be governed by a Master, three Wardens and ten or more Assistants who would form the Court. The first Master was [[David Ramsay (watchmaker)|David Ramsay]], a Scot, who had been appointed watchmaker to [[James VI of Scotland]], later James I of England. The noted clockmaker [[Edward East (clockmaker)|Edward East]] also formed part of the first Court.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Some Account of the Worshipful Company of Clockmakers|last=Atkins|first=Samuel|publisher=|year=1881|location=London|pages=8}}</ref>\n\nThe original Charter is still in the company's possession and is housed with the rest of its library and archive in the Guildhall Library.<ref>See the catalogue of the London Metropolitan Archive, reference CLC/L/CD</ref>\nThe company obtained a [[grant of arms]] from the [[College of Arms]] in January 1672. In 1766, the [[Court of Aldermen]] granted the Company its livery. The number of Liverymen was originally limited at sixty but has been increased in number over the years by approval of the [[City of London Corporation]] and currently stands at a maximum of three hundred.<ref>http://www.clockmakers.org/history-customs/freedom-and-livery/</ref>\n\n==Horological Training and Awards for Excellence==\nThe company bestows three awards for excellence: the Tompion Medal for outstanding achievements in horology, the Harrison Medal for the propagation of horological knowledge and its appreciation, and the Derek Pratt Prize for innovation, ingenuity, elegance, and the highest standards of workmanship and precision performance in the craft and science of time and timekeeping.\nThe company also closely co-operates with the trustees of the [[George Daniels (watchmaker)|George Daniels]] Educational Trust in supporting education in horology.\n\n==Affiliations==\nThe Clockmakers Company is formally affiliated with the [[Antiquarian Horological Society]], the [[UCL Observatory]], [[HMS Protector (A173)|HMS ''Protector'']], the Royal Navy's Ice Patrol Ship.<ref>http://www.clockmakers.org/about/affiliations/</ref> and [[HMS Archer|HMS ''Archer'']], a P264 Class University Royal Naval Unit based in Edinburgh.\n\n==Masters==\n[[File:Reverend Henry Leonard Nelthropp.jpg|thumb|The Reverend Henry Leonard Nelthropp MA FSA, Master of the Worshipful Company of Clockmakers of the City of London 1893 and 1894.]]\n[[File:City of London, unusually arranged clock - geograph.org.uk - 559842.jpg|thumb|The [[Newgate|Newgate Street]] clock, the Worshipful Company of Clockmakers' 375th anniversary gift to the City of London.]]\nThose who have been Master of the company include the following:<ref>[http://www.clockmakers.org/about/the-court-committees-panels/masters-since-1631/ Masters since 1631], The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers website, accessed 06/02/2011</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*1631, [[David Ramsay (watchmaker)|David Ramsay]]\n*1636, [[Elias Allen]]\n*1645, 1652 [[Edward East (clockmaker)|Edward East]]\n*1700, [[Charles Gretton]]<ref>[Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''Charles Gretton: Clock & Watchmaking Through The Golden Age''. Vancouver, Canada: Three O'clock Publishing. {{ISBN|978-0-9940460-0-0}}. https://www.grettonbook.com</ref>\n*1702, [[Joseph Windmills]]\n*1703, [[Thomas Tompion]]\n*1708, [[Daniel Quare]]\n*1717 Nathaniel Chamberlain \n*1718, [[Joseph Windmills|Thomas Windmills]]\n*1817, [[John Roger Arnold]]\n*1821, 1823, 1825, 1827, 1847 [[Benjamin Lewis Vulliamy]]\n*1855, 1862 [[Charles Frodsham]]\n*1893, 1894 Revd. Henry Leonard Nelthropp\n*1902, 1914 [[William Henry Mahoney Christie]] KCB FRS\n*1922, 1931 Sir [[Frank Watson Dyson]] KBE FRS FRSE\n*1926, [[Hugh Rotherham]]\n*1946, [[Edward Iliffe, 1st Baron Iliffe|Lord Iliffe of Yattendon]] GBE\n*1949, 1954 Sir [[Harold Spencer Jones]] KBE FRS FRSE PRAS\n*1950, [[William Hamilton Shortt]] FBHI\n*1959, [[Viscount Falmouth]]\n*1960, [[Baron Harris|Lord Harris]]\n*1969, Sir [[Richard van der Riet Woolley]] OBE FRS\n*1974, Sir [[Frank Chalton Francis]] KCB\n*1976, Sir [[Hugh Wontner]] GBE CVO\n*1980, [[George Daniels (watchmaker)|George Daniels]] CBE DSc FBHI FSA AHCI\n*1986, [[Viscount Falmouth]]\n*1989, [[Lord Murton of Lindisfarne]] OBE TD PC\n*2000, [[Alexander Boksenberg]] CBE FRS\n*2001, Sir George White, Bt, FSA\n*2002, Michael Monro Smith\n*2003, Christopher John Hurrion\n*2004, Philip John Willoughby\n*2005, Diana Muriel Uff\n*2006, [[David Pennefather|Maj Gen David Anthony Somerset Pennefather CB OBE]]\n*2007, David John Poole FBHI\n*2008, Dr Michael David Sanderson PhD\n*2009, Cdr Peter John Linstead-Smith OBE RN\n*2010, Howard Carl Newman FBHI\n*2011, Andrew Charles Henry Crisford FSA\n*2012, Mark Westcombe Elliott FCA\n*2013, Prof Paul Eugene Marcus Jarrett FRCS\n*2014, [[Jonathan Betts|Jonathan Daniel Betts MBE FSA FBHI]]\n*2015, Philip William Tennant Whyte, Hon FBHI\n*2016, Robert Michael Justice Stewart\n*2017, Roy Charles Harris, FBHI\n*2018, Andrew Lewis James, FRSA, Hon MBHI\n*2019, Jonathan Edward Hills\n*2020, Joanna Migdal (Lady White)\n{{colend}}\n{{Expand list|date=September 2017}}\n\n==Company Chaplains and Church==\n* Reverend Hugh Bearn <ref>http://liverydatabase.liverycompanies.info/networks/553/index.html</ref>\n* [[St James Garlickhythe]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=160px>\nFile:Wenceslas Hollar - Elias Allen.jpg|[[Elias Allen]]\nFile:Thomas Tompion00.jpg|[[Thomas Tompion]]\nFile:John Arnold.jpg|[[John Arnold (watchmaker)|John Arnold]]\nFile:Charles Frodsham.gif|[[Charles Frodsham]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[British Horological Institute]]\n*[[Clockmakers' Museum]]\n*[[Antiquarian Horological Society]]\n*[[Charles Gretton]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.grettonbook.com/home The Gretton Project]: Research endeavour and book (''THROUGH THE GOLDEN AGE \u2013 Charles Gretton \u2013 Watch and Clockmaking'', published 2016) about clockmaker and watchmaker [[Charles Gretton]], who was Master of the Clockmakers' Company in 1700. The book contains a substantial historical introduction as well as historical appendices, providing considerable information about the Company in the late 17th and early 18th centuries.\n*[http://www.clockmakers.org/ The Clockmakers' Company]\n\n{{Livery Companies in the City of London}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Worshipful Company Of Clockmakers}}\n[[Category:Livery companies|Clockmakers]]\n[[Category:Horology]]\n[[Category:1631 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Time in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Horological organizations]]\n[[Category:Clocks]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox Livery Company\n| name        = Worshipful Company of Clockmakers\n| image       = Clockmakers Company Coat of Arms.jpg\n| caption     = Arms of the Clockmakers' Company, granted in January 1672. Blazon: ''Sable, a Clock ye Four Pillars thereof Erected on Four Lyons, and on Each Capital a Globe with a Cross, and in the Middest an Imperiall Crowne all Or, and for their Crest upon an Helmet Proper Mantled Gules Doubled Argent and Wreath of their Colours a Spheare Or, the Armes Supported by the Figures of a Naked Old Man Holding a Scithe and an Hour Glasse Representing Time, and of an Emperour in Roabes Crowned Holding a Scepter.''\n| motto       = ''Tempus Rerum Imperator''\n| location    = 1 Throgmorton Avenue, London EC2N 2BY\n| formation   = {{start date|df=yes|1631}}\n| association = Horology\n| precedence  = 61st\n| master      = Joanna Migdal (Lady White)\n| website     = {{url|clockmakers.org}}\n}}\n{{short description|Livery company of the City of London}}\nThe '''Worshipful Company of Clockmakers''' was established under a [[Royal Charter]] granted by [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] in 1631.<ref>https://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/royal-charters/list-of-charters-granted/</ref> It ranks sixty-first among the [[livery companies]] of the City of London, and comes under the jurisdiction of the [[Privy Council]]. The company established a library and its [[Clockmakers' Museum|Museum]] in 1813, which is the oldest specific collection of clocks and watches worldwide.<ref>https://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/see-and-do/clockmakers-museum</ref> This is administered by the company's affiliated charity, the Clockmakers\u2019 Charity,<ref>Charity No. 275380 registered with the UK Charity Commission</ref> and is presently housed on the second floor of London's [[Science Museum, London|Science Museum]]. The modern aims of the company and its Museum are charitable and educational, in particular to promote and preserve clockmaking and watchmaking, which as of 2019 were added to the [[HCA Red List of Endangered Crafts]].\n\n==Museum==\nThe [[Clockmakers' Museum|Clockmakers\u2019 Museum]], first established in 1813, was housed at London's [[Guildhall, London|Guildhall]] from 1874 to 2014. The collection of clocks and watches was moved to a new gallery provided by the Science Museum, officially opened by HRH [[Princess Anne]] on 22 October 2015. The company's archive and library are however still kept at [[Guildhall Library]]. The collection includes [[John Harrison|John Harrison's]] sea watch H5, once personally tested by [[King George III]].\n\n==Motto==\nThe company's motto, ''Tempus Rerum Imperator'', can be translated as \u2018Time, the Ruler of All Things\u2019. It appears as an epitaph on the tombstone of former British Prime Minister [[Harold Wilson]], a liveryman of the company. It has also been adopted by the [[Google Web Accelerator]] project.\n\n==History==\nPrior to the seventeenth century, clockmaking by native English craftsmen was mostly confined to the production of [[turret clocks]]. Domestic clocks and watches were mostly imported or the work of immigrants from the Continent. Because turret clock making involved working in ferrous metal, clockmakers within the City of London tended to be freemen of the [[Worshipful Company of Blacksmiths|Blacksmiths\u2019 Company]], though some were members of other livery companies, notably the [[Worshipful Company of Clothworkers|Clothworkers]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=English Lantern Clocks|last=White|first=George|publisher=ACC|year=1989|location=|pages=51\u201354}}</ref>\n\nAfter the loss of many London clock and watchmakers in the plagues of 1598 and 1603, the trade consolidated and began to grow. The continued influx of newcomers led to resentment from those who had become established in London towards outsiders who came to set up in or near the City and who threatened their market. From 1620 onwards, groups of clockmakers attempted to set up their own guild. The Blacksmiths initially succeeded in opposing these moves. Eventually, however, with the King issuing charters as a means of raising much needed finance at a time when he had prorogued Parliament, the clockmakers succeeded in securing a Royal Charter, on 22 August 1631, to the distress of the Blacksmiths, who could naturally expect to lose members, and therefore income.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Clockmakers of London|last=White|first=George|publisher=WCC|year=2018|location=London|pages=14\u201319}}</ref>\n\nThe Charter gave regulatory authority to the Clockmakers to control the horological trade in the City of London and for a radius of ten miles around. It incorporated a controlling body which should have \u2018continuance for ever under the style and name of The Master, Wardens and Fellowship of the Art and Mystery of Clockmaking\u2019. It provided that the Fellowship should be governed by a Master, three Wardens and ten or more Assistants who would form the Court. The first Master was [[David Ramsay (watchmaker)|David Ramsay]], a Scot, who had been appointed watchmaker to [[James VI of Scotland]], later James I of England. The noted clockmaker [[Edward East (clockmaker)|Edward East]] also formed part of the first Court.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Some Account of the Worshipful Company of Clockmakers|last=Atkins|first=Samuel|publisher=|year=1881|location=London|pages=8}}</ref>\n\nThe original Charter is still in the company's possession and is housed with the rest of its library and archive in the Guildhall Library.<ref>See the catalogue of the London Metropolitan Archive, reference CLC/L/CD</ref>\nThe company obtained a [[grant of arms]] from the [[College of Arms]] in January 1672. In 1766, the [[Court of Aldermen]] granted the Company its livery. The number of Liverymen was originally limited at sixty but has been increased in number over the years by approval of the [[City of London Corporation]] and currently stands at a maximum of three hundred.<ref>http://www.clockmakers.org/history-customs/freedom-and-livery/</ref>\n\n==Horological Training and Awards for Excellence==\nThe company bestows three awards for excellence: the Tompion Medal for outstanding achievements in horology, the Harrison Medal for the propagation of horological knowledge and its appreciation, and the Derek Pratt Prize for innovation, ingenuity, elegance, and the highest standards of workmanship and precision performance in the craft and science of time and timekeeping.\nThe company also closely co-operates with the trustees of the [[George Daniels (watchmaker)|George Daniels]] Educational Trust in supporting education in horology.\n\n==Affiliations==\nThe Clockmakers Company is formally affiliated with the [[Antiquarian Horological Society]], the [[UCL Observatory]], [[HMS Protector (A173)|HMS ''Protector'']], the Royal Navy's Ice Patrol Ship.<ref>http://www.clockmakers.org/about/affiliations/</ref> and [[HMS Archer|HMS ''Archer'']], a P264 Class University Royal Naval Unit based in Edinburgh.\n\n==Masters==\n[[File:Reverend Henry Leonard Nelthropp.jpg|thumb|The Reverend Henry Leonard Nelthropp MA FSA, Master of the Worshipful Company of Clockmakers of the City of London 1893 and 1894.]]\n[[File:City of London, unusually arranged clock - geograph.org.uk - 559842.jpg|thumb|The [[Newgate|Newgate Street]] clock, the Worshipful Company of Clockmakers' 375th anniversary gift to the City of London.]]\nThose who have been Master of the company include the following:<ref>[http://www.clockmakers.org/about/the-court-committees-panels/masters-since-1631/ Masters since 1631], The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers website, accessed 06/02/2011</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*1631, [[David Ramsay (watchmaker)|David Ramsay]]\n*1636, [[Elias Allen]]\n*1645, 1652 [[Edward East (clockmaker)|Edward East]]\n*1700, [[Charles Gretton]]<ref>[Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''Charles Gretton: Clock & Watchmaking Through The Golden Age''. Vancouver, Canada: Three O'clock Publishing. {{ISBN|978-0-9940460-0-0}}. https://www.grettonbook.com</ref>\n*1702, [[Joseph Windmills]]\n*1703, [[Thomas Tompion]]\n*1708, [[Daniel Quare]]\n*1717 Nathaniel Chamberlain \n*1718, [[Joseph Windmills|Thomas Windmills]]\n*1817, [[John Roger Arnold]]\n*1821, 1823, 1825, 1827, 1847 [[Benjamin Lewis Vulliamy]]\n*1855, 1862 [[Charles Frodsham]]\n*1893, 1894 Revd. Henry Leonard Nelthropp\n*1902, 1914 [[William Henry Mahoney Christie]] KCB FRS\n*1922, 1931 Sir [[Frank Watson Dyson]] KBE FRS FRSE\n*1926, [[Hugh Rotherham]]\n*1946, [[Edward Iliffe, 1st Baron Iliffe|Lord Iliffe of Yattendon]] GBE\n*1949, 1954 Sir [[Harold Spencer Jones]] KBE FRS FRSE PRAS\n*1950, [[William Hamilton Shortt]] FBHI\n*1959, [[Viscount Falmouth]]\n*1960, [[Baron Harris|Lord Harris]]\n*1969, Sir [[Richard van der Riet Woolley]] OBE FRS\n*1974, Sir [[Frank Chalton Francis]] KCB\n*1976, Sir [[Hugh Wontner]] GBE CVO\n*1980, [[George Daniels (watchmaker)|George Daniels]] CBE DSc FBHI FSA AHCI\n*1986, [[Viscount Falmouth]]\n*1989, [[Lord Murton of Lindisfarne]] OBE TD PC\n*2000, [[Alexander Boksenberg]] CBE FRS\n*2001, Sir George White, Bt, FSA\n*2002, Michael Monro Smith\n*2003, Christopher John Hurrion\n*2004, Philip John Willoughby\n*2005, Diana Muriel Uff\n*2006, [[David Pennefather|Maj Gen David Anthony Somerset Pennefather CB OBE]]\n*2007, David John Poole FBHI\n*2008, Dr Michael David Sanderson PhD\n*2009, Cdr Peter John Linstead-Smith OBE RN\n*2010, Howard Carl Newman FBHI\n*2011, Andrew Charles Henry Crisford FSA\n*2012, Mark Westcombe Elliott FCA\n*2013, Prof Paul Eugene Marcus Jarrett FRCS\n*2014, [[Jonathan Betts|Jonathan Daniel Betts MBE FSA FBHI]]\n*2015, Philip William Tennant Whyte, Hon FBHI\n*2016, Robert Michael Justice Stewart\n*2017, Roy Charles Harris, FBHI\n*2018, Andrew Lewis James, FRSA, Hon MBHI\n*2019, Jonathan Edward Hills\n*2020, Joanna Migdal (Lady White)\n{{colend}}\n{{Expand list|date=September 2017}}\n\n==Company Chaplains and Church==\n* Reverend Hugh Bearn <ref>http://liverydatabase.liverycompanies.info/networks/553/index.html</ref>\n* [[St James Garlickhythe]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=160px>\nFile:Wenceslas Hollar - Elias Allen.jpg|[[Elias Allen]]\nFile:Thomas Tompion00.jpg|[[Thomas Tompion]]\nFile:John Arnold.jpg|[[John Arnold (watchmaker)|John Arnold]]\nFile:Charles Frodsham.gif|[[Charles Frodsham]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[British Horological Institute]]\n*[[Clockmakers' Museum]]\n*[[Antiquarian Horological Society]]\n*[[Charles Gretton]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.grettonbook.com/home The Gretton Project]: Research endeavour and book (''THROUGH THE GOLDEN AGE \u2013 Charles Gretton \u2013 Watch and Clockmaking'', published 2016) about clockmaker and watchmaker [[Charles Gretton]], who was Master of the Clockmakers' Company in 1700. The book's historical introduction contains considerable information about the Company in the late 17th and early 18th centuries.\n*[http://www.clockmakers.org/ The Clockmakers' Company]\n\n{{Livery Companies in the City of London}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Worshipful Company Of Clockmakers}}\n[[Category:Livery companies|Clockmakers]]\n[[Category:Horology]]\n[[Category:1631 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Time in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Horological organizations]]\n[[Category:Clocks]]\n", "name_user": "Dania.Sheldon", "label": "safe", "comment": "adjusted wording in one external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Worshipful_Company_of_Clockmakers"}
{"title_page": "Lee and Herring", "text_new": "{{about|the duo themselves|their self-titled radio series|Lee and Herring (radio series)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[File:Leeandherring.jpg|thumb|right]] -->\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name            = Lee and Herring\n| image           = {{Image array\n| perrow = 2\n| image1 = StewartLee.jpg\n| image2 = Richard Herring (cropped).jpg\n| width = 130\n| height = 200\n}}\n| image_size      = \n| caption         = Lee (left, 2008) and Herring (right, 2005)\n| medium          = [[Television]], [[Radio]], [[Stand-up comedy|Stand-up]]\n| nationality     = [[British nationality law|British]]\n| years_active    = 1992\u20132000<!-- the first instance i can find suggests that they were not a double act per se until they left 'On The Hour' in 1991. -->\n| genre           = [[Sketch comedy]]<br>[[Black comedy]]<br>[[Surreal humour]]<br>[[Wit]]<br>[[Satire]]\n| subject         = [[Culture of the United Kingdom|British culture]]<br>[[Everyday life]]\n<!-- Infobox comedian does not support the following parameter:\n| influences      = [[Monty Python]]<br>[[Ted Chippington]]\n-->\n| notable_works   = ''[[Fist of Fun]]''<br>''[[This Morning with Richard Not Judy]]''<br>''[[Real Time (Doctor Who)]]''\n| current_members = [[Richard Herring]] <br> [[Stewart Lee]]\n| website         = \n| footnotes       = \n}}\n\n'''Lee and Herring''' were a British standup comedy [[double act]] consisting of the comedians [[Stewart Lee]] and [[Richard Herring]]. They were most famous for their work on television, most notably ''[[Fist of Fun]]'' and ''[[This Morning with Richard Not Judy]]'' but had  been working together on stage and on radio since the late 1980s.\n\nAs with many double acts, Lee and Herring performed as contrasting personalities: one mature and duplicitous (Lee) and the other puerile and cheeky (Herring). As with several other double acts, Lee and Herring had a certain [[irony]] to their style and constantly checked themselves and made reference to this. The characters of Lee and Herring were [[parody|parodies]] and exaggerations of their real life selves.\n\nIn 2011, [[Frank Skinner]] cited Lee and Herring as one of his favourite comedy double acts, alongside [[Laurel and Hardy]], [[The Two Ronnies]] and [[Reeves and Mortimer]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Frank Skinner |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/home/moslive/article-2082122/The-Two-Ronnies-Reeves--Mortimer-The-greatest-comedy-double-acts.html |title=The Two Ronnies to Reeves & Mortimer: The top ten greatest comedy double acts &#124; Mail Online |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date=2012-01-07 |accessdate=2014-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nLee and Herring first met at a party while they were studying at [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/how-we-met-stewart-lee-richard-herring-1088166.html|title=How we met: Stewart Lee & Richard Herring|date=18 April 1999|author=Laurence Phelan|website=The Independent|access-date=10 December 2019}}</ref> Lee had been performing stand-up on the circuit for a short while and had heard that Herring had been trying to as well, so he introduced himself. Lee once remarked that one of the reasons they decided to work as a double act was that they found the resemblance of the title \"Lee and Herring\" to [[Worcestershire sauce]] brand [[Lea & Perrins]] humorous.\n\nAt Oxford, Lee and Herring performed in a regular comedy revue called The [[Seven Raymonds]], which also included the material and performance of [[Emma Kennedy]], Michael Cosgrave and [[Tim Richardson (writer)|Tim Richardson]].\n\nTogether they wrote material for [[Chris Morris (satirist)|Chris Morris]]' ''[[On The Hour]]'' (1991). However, a management conflict meant that the duo were not involved in the television version, ''[[The Day Today]]'', and that their material was edited out of the original official BBC audio releases of ''On The Hour'' (it was later re-instated in a 2009 CD release on [[Warp Records]].\n\nIn 1992 and 1993, they wrote and performed ''[[Lionel Nimrod's Inexplicable World]]'' for [[BBC Radio 4]]. For [[BBC Radio 1]], they wrote and performed one series of ''[[Fist of Fun]]'' (1993), which later transferred to television and would pave the way for their mainstream success. ''Fist of Fun'' made several subtle references to their dislike for former colleague [[Patrick Marber]]. Lee and Herring fell out with the ''On The Hour'' team after a row over ownership of characters; Patrick Marber has claimed that he invented the character of news reporter [[Peter O'Hanraha-hanrahan]], while Lee and Herring also claim to have invented the character.<ref>A text box in Fist of Fun's first series.</ref>\n\nAfter the radio version of ''Fist of Fun'', they presented another Radio 1 show running for 3 series, simply entitled ''[[Lee and Herring (radio series)|Lee and Herring]]'' (but often referred to as ''Lee & Herring's Radio One Music Show'') which featured a mixture of records chosen by the duo themselves, and their comedy sketches and discussions.\n\nTheir final major work as a double-act was ''[[This Morning With Richard Not Judy]]'' (''TMWRNJ''), which aired on Sunday mornings on [[BBC Two]] for series in 1998 and 1999, and was famous{{citation needed|date=March 2012}} for being increasingly risqu\u00e9 and original.\n\n==Break-up==\nLee and Herring went their separate ways at the end of the 1990s and have both enjoyed major fringe and mainstream fame. Stewart Lee retired from stand-up comedy in the early 2000s, a time in which he co-wrote ''[[Jerry Springer - The Opera]]'' and directed ''[[Attention Scum!]]'' for [[Simon Munnery]]. He made a comeback to stand-up in 2005, touring very successful shows, and has written and performed four series of his own [[BBC 2]] television show ''[[Stewart Lee's Comedy Vehicle]]''.\n\nRichard Herring went on to write the sitcoms ''[[Time Gentlemen Please]]'' for [[Sky One]] with [[Al Murray]], and ''You Can Choose Your Friends'' (which was loosely based on his own family) for [[ITV Network|ITV]], and worked on the third series of ''[[Little Britain]]'' as script editor. Herring has written, performed and toured with a number of successful comedy shows including ''Christ on a Bike'', ''Hitler Moustache'' and ''We're All Going To Die'', building up an audience through the medium of podcasts which include ''[[Collings and Herrin (podcast)|Collings and Herrin]]'' with Andrew Collins and his interview show ''[[Richard Herring Interviews|Richard Herring's Leicester Square Theatre Podcast]]''. 2013 is his 22nd year at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]], where he has performed 10 different stand-up shows in as many years.\n\n==Reunions==\n\nLee and Herring occasionally reunite for one-off events. Recent collaborations include an interview together for ''[[The Guardian]]'' and a 2005 review of each other's work for the arts supplement of ''[[The Sunday Times]]''.\n\nThe pair performed a short set at [[London]]'s [[Bloomsbury Theatre]] on 5 February 2007 as part of a tribute to stand-up comedian [[Ted Chippington]].\n\nThey reunited for a 30-minute performance at the [[Lyric Theatre (Hammersmith)|Lyric Theatre]] in [[Hammersmith]] on 16 November 2008, where they were joined at the end by a resurrected \"Curious Orange\".<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2008/nov/18/comedy</ref>\n\nA brief reunion took place at the 2010 Edinburgh Fringe at Stewart Lee's ''Silver Stewbilee'' show in which Herring heckled him and ran on stage, berating him for his \"pretentious\" new book.<ref>http://www.chortle.co.uk/shows/edinburgh_fringe_2010/s/17776/stewart_lee%3A_silver_stewbilee/review</ref> Lee also \"appeared\" as a recorded [[voicemail]] message on ''[[The Collings and Herrin Podcast]] Live'' the following day.\n\nHerring interviewed Lee in June 2012 on his series ''[[Richard Herring's Leicester Square Theatre Podcast]]''. The filmed version of this encounter has both an individual release by indie company [[Go Faster Stripe]], and acts as extra material on the Series Two ''Fist of Fun'' box set. Other podcast appearances between the two include ''Richard Herring's Edinburgh Fringe Podcast'' in August 2013 and again for the sixth season of Richard Herring's Leicester Square Theatre Podcast in 2015.\n\nOn 2 June 2014, Lee and Herring briefly appeared on stage together when Lee introduced Herring's section at a [[British Humanist Association]] benefit.<ref>http://www.richardherring.com/warmingup/2/6/2014/index.html</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\n===Live===\n*''Lionel Nimrod's Inexplicable World - LIVE!''<ref>http://www.fistoffun.net/live.php</ref>\n*''This Morning With Richard Not Judy'' (1994)\n*''Lee and Herring Live off of TV's Fist of Fun'' (1995)\n*''Lee & Herring Live'' (1996)\n*''This Morning With Richard Not Judy II'' (1997)\n*''Lee and Herring'' (1998)<ref>http://www.richardherring.com/press/8430/edinburgh_show_list.html</ref>\n\n===Radio===\n*''The End of the Roadshow'' (1992)<ref>http://www.fistoffun.net/downloads-endoftheroadshow.php</ref>\n*''[[On the Hour]]'' (1991\u201392)\n*''[[Lionel Nimrod's Inexplicable World]]'' (1992\u201393)\n*''[[Fist of Fun]]'' (1993)\n*''[[Lee and Herring (radio series)|Lee and Herring]]'' (Lee & Herring's [[BBC Radio One|Radio One]] Music Show) (1994\u201395)\n\n===Television===\n*''[[Fist of Fun]]'' (1995\u201396)\n*''Festival of Fun'' (1995)\n*''Lee & Herring's Reasonably Scary Monsters'' (1998)\n*''[[This Morning With Richard Not Judy]]'' (1998\u201399)\n\n===Books===\n* ''Lee & Herring's Fist of Fun'' (1995) BBC Books\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.leeandherring.com/ Lee and Herring.com]\n*[http://www.stewartlee.co.uk/ Stewart Lee's website]\n*[http://www.richardherring.com/ Richard Herring's website]\n*[http://www.fistoffun.net/ ''Fist of Fun''.net] fansite, includes downloads of their radio shows and live performances, episode guides, interviews, etc.\n*{{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202160125/http://www.offthetelly.co.uk/interviews/leeherring.htm |title=Off the Telly Steve Williams talks to Lee and Herring }}\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2008/nov/18/comedy Guardian review] Brian Logan reviews Lyric gig 2008\n*[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/stage/comedy/article5173915.ece Times] Dominic Maxwell reviews Lyric gig 2008\n\n{{Lee and Herring}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Herring, Lee And}}\n[[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:English male actors]]\n[[Category:English comedy duos]]\n[[Category:British comedy duos]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the duo themselves|their self-titled radio series|Lee and Herring (radio series)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[File:Leeandherring.jpg|thumb|right]] -->\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name            = Lee and Herring\n| image           = {{Image array\n| perrow = 2\n| image1 = StewartLee.jpg\n| image2 = Richard Herring (cropped).jpg\n| width = 130\n| height = 200\n}}\n| image_size      = \n| caption         = Lee (left, 2008) and Herring (right, 2005)\n| medium          = [[Television]], [[Radio]], [[Stand-up comedy|Stand-up]]\n| nationality     = [[British nationality law|British]]\n| years_active    = 1992\u20132000<!-- the first instance i can find suggests that they were not a double act per se until they left 'On The Hour' in 1991. -->\n| genre           = [[Sketch comedy]]<br>[[Black comedy]]<br>[[Surreal humour]]<br>[[Wit]]<br>[[Satire]]\n| subject         = [[Culture of the United Kingdom|British culture]]<br>[[Everyday life]]\n<!-- Infobox comedian does not support the following parameter:\n| influences      = [[Monty Python]]<br>[[Ted Chippington]]\n-->\n| notable_works   = ''[[Fist of Fun]]''<br>''[[Th